Spotlight is a movie that I didn't think I would want to watch more than once because of it's subject matter but I can't help myself with Tom McCarthy's masterpiece. It does what The Post should have done, it keeps the integrity of the story and keeps you locked in for the full 2hr run time. The brilliant ensemble cast doesn't try to out do one another but rather leans on the material and lets the story speak for itself.
9.5/10, well acted and riveting
Spotlight was ok, but devoid of any tension, ambiguity, depth, complexity. We all know the story---the reality---that 90 priests molested and/or had inappropriate sexual interactions with teen and preteens, and that the Catholic Church in Boston and elsewhere covered it up. But this take on that story is about how a principled Jewish editor in chief (played by an apparently bored Liev Schreiber) arrives at the Boston Globe and is the only one who can see injustice and responsible journalism with any clarity, and how it was his moral backbone and intellectual prowess that enabled taking down the Catholic Church when none had dared or been able to do so before--and how many had resisted and/or actively fought against the real story to come out. The acting is uniformly good--it should be; it's a stellar cast--but the whole thing is turned down so low, so drably, so one dimensionally, it is very hard to keep watching and listening to the same lectures over and over (and over and over) for over 2 hours.  There needed to be a reality check--or a devil's advocate--or some other POV beyond the obvious one that is hammered without deviation from the following: molesting children is evil, Catholic priests molested children, the Catholic Church is all over the world, therefore unspeakable evils have unfolded to unfathomable numbers of kids worldwide thanks to the Catholic Church, which must be stopped--and thank goodness for the 100% good, brave, intellectually clean and clear "outsiders" who step forward valiantly to put a stop to evils like Catholicism. Little shortcuts like "Gasp!!! Lawyers who approached the Catholic Church with allegations of abuse for many years did not officially file lawsuits in court?!! Nor did they go to the media?!!! There are nondisclosure agreements with the people who settled with the church---egad!!" Doesn't take into account that 90% of lawsuits against corporations, organizations, universities, and individuals are treated precisely that way. Is it to "cover up what happened," as a conspiracy?  Not necessarily---that is the way that legal action often/usually unfolds--out of court settlements, "mediation," arbitration. And almost always as part of those settlements is a non-disclosure agreement.  It is not unusual--the way this film makes it out to be--that the Catholic Church did something bizarrely untoward each time they were approached with a claim, for their attorneys to work with the plaintiff's attorneys and not to go to the media with it. Not to say the Catholic Church handled--or handles---such things appropriately. But many times in Spotlight actions like the preceding example of settling out of court is conflated with corruption, nefariousness, conspiracy. The Church may be and have been corrupt and nefarious--and even perpetuated conspiracy--but why not climb a bit farther inside it and show how the very people thinking they were doing the right thing were completely wrong-minded about it? THAT in itself is far more arresting and affecting than watching a painfully out of tune children's choir warbe "Silent Night" in a shadowy church, watched over by a priest, while Mark Ruffalo stands in the unwatched darkness, a single tear dribbling down his cheek. Heavy-handed and unnuanced missed opportunity. For an exponentially more effective film on this topic, see "Doubt." That will haunt you. Spotlight, in contrast, will most likely sort of bore you (which you'll then have to deny since it's such a dire topic).
Thrilling! One of my favorite movie of all time.
