good cast and a great story based on real life story in Boston about the Catholic church
Following in the footsteps of other journalistic drama greats like "All The President's Men" and "The Insider" before it, this Best Picture winner takes an incredibly engrossing story of investigative passion and layers a thick coating of moral intrigue and subtle, yet effective emotionality on top of it. Sure, "Spotlight" may lack the directorial panache and flair that other, admittedly more complete films would possess, but I'll be damned if the subject matter at hand doesn't elevate everything in play. I don't need this to be flashy or expressive. The message and story at hand do it all for me. And what a story it is, scripted beautifully by Josh Singer and director Tom McCarthy, featuring stellar dialogue, brilliantly vibrant scene dynamics, and -- again -- a call to action that'll knock you on your back. "Spotlight" shocked me in nearly every way imaginable. Not only is it a well-deserved candidate for the best movie of 2015, it's a well-deserved candidate for being one of the best movies of its kind.
Great casting though I think that McAdams could've done a better job 
Really well done. Amazing so many people would look the other way. 
As I've watched an ever-increasing number of films across a variety of genres, I've come to the conclusion that the investigative drama is one of my favorite genres. My favorite movies in this genre are those which are simultaneously low key and suspenseful. Films such as The Third Murder, Rear Window, and The Conversation maintain high levels of tension with a minimum of onscreen violence, achieving the type of audience engagement I'd associate with a high body count thriller with a more measured, intellectual tone. Spotlight is, undoubtedly, one of the best films of the genre I've ever seen. Following the titular "Spotlight" team from The Boston Globe as they investigate what could be the biggest story of their career, a child abuse scandal involving the Catholic Church, the film is extremely tense, yet simultaneously low key, creating an extremely engaging drama without sacrificing the air of authenticity demanded by an adaptation of a true story.

The movie features one of the strongest ensemble casts I have ever seen, to the point that pointing out standouts is very hard because of the inspired performances all around. In a clever bit of directing, these characters are frequently towered over by edifices symbolizing the very organization the team is investigating as they exchange dialogue. This dialogue is engaging not just because of the acting prowess on display, but also because movie also has an excellent script. I particularly like the use of subtext and doublespeak in the film. While the film does not convey as many layers of meaning in a single sentence as Tokyo Story, which I have praised for similar reasons, it acknowledges that it is often counterproductive for a reporter to get accusatory and openly angry with interviewees and that, for the person on the other end of the notepad, threats should not be made openly and publicly, especially towards someone in the position to publish those threats. These are aspects of the profession commonly ignored by films featuring reporters.

I suspect some people will find the film to be anti-religious. I didn't get that impression. Spotlight certainly does not portray the Catholic Church as an institution in a positive manner, but it does not attack its God directly, only the mortals ostensibly in God's service. Throughout the film, the "Spotlight" team conduct repeated telephone interviews with a former Catholic priest who became a critic of the Church due to their handling of sexual abuse claims. He has little positive to say about the people running the church, but still considers himself a Catholic. Even if we assume the existence of an infallible god, humans, those who claim to be servants of that deity may still commit immoral actions, and those acts should not be excused because the evildoer is a priest. Spotlight takes no definite stance on religion, only on those who use it to conceal their own evil acts.

This movie was flat, boring, and seemed just clinical and surgical in the way it dealt with such a tragic and controversial topic. I can't believe such a careless and boring snooze-fest won best picture. 
An Academy Award winner for Best Picture and an excellent film that gives one a good idea of the code of silence and the vastness of the problem of sexual abuse of children by priests on a scale most of us could never imagine. Any respect I had for the Catholic Church  and its hierarchy is gone, leaving in its place nothing but disgust that the Church protected such horrendous monsters, not as any forgiveness due to sinners who preyed on the most vulnerable that the Church should have protected at all costs, but to salve it's own pride--one of the 7 Deadly Sins! What overwhelming hypocrisy, the worst a religious group could ever commit! because it preyed on children and ruined all of their young lives in the very worst criminal way! There is no excuse and never could be!
Very good movie, try to detail the facts but in some cases make excessive use of the resource of put crying people in the screen but in general is a spectacular movie.
Spotlight is one of the most important films of my lifetime. The story is so significant, and Spotlight honors it in a near-perfect way.
The most beloved films about journalists, All the President's Men (1976) and Cry Freedom (1987) portray them almost like action heroes as they intelligently interrogate shadowy figures whilst bonding with their partner or righteously campaign for the civil rights of a racially oppressed group. Spotlight avoids all of this portraying it's heroes as able and worthy in their jobs as they face a difficult task but they always feel very grounded and big, teary-eyed speeches about "integrity" and "truth" are never brought out to sell the idea that journalism is important, we already understand. Although I didn't love the film it tells a story about an important subject matter with grace and intelligence not seen in many √Ø¬ø 1/2 1/2 1/2~based on a true story' Best Picture winners.

The √Ø¬ø 1/2 1/2 1/2~Spotlight' team work at the Boston Herald on big exposes as they spend months, sometimes years on single stories as they compile irrefutable evidence to back up their claims. The enemy that they face this time is the Catholic Church as they block them at every turn in their attempt to access sealed information about covered up child abuse within the Boston diocese. Walter Robinson, Michael Keaton, Michael Rezendes, Mark Ruffalo, Sacha Pfeiffer and Rachel McAdams band together in their intrepid investigation of the case and discover just how deep the corruption goes whilst collecting heartrending testimonies from victims.

The most affecting moments in the film are of course the confessions from the mostly adult victims of sexual abuse as they describe how they and those around them were manipulated into beginning sexual relationships with priests. The attempts that they made to have these dangerous figures removed from positions of power failed as the system is set up to prevent their stories from getting out. The victims are played well by unknown actors as the emotions are clear upon their faces but there are no dramatic outbursts or sudden revelations that cause them to cry out in pain and terror. No, we get hard, simple truths about the endless terrors of child sexual abuse as we witness that one prominent victim had at some point fallen victim to a cocaine habit. This has more emotional resonance than any scene from The Accused (1988) where Jodie Foster cries out due to her trauma. These characters stay with us and it is their pain that motivates both the journalists and the audience in revealing this abuse to the public and dethroning these villainous abusers.

The reporting is also seen to come not from eureka moments or a natural talent for composing alliterative sentences but from honest work. We see journalists plugging away at all hours, doing the dull work of filling in spreadsheets and writing comprehensive notes during long interviews. We also get dramatic scenes of Keaton confronting his close high school friend who may be closely connected to the cover up but these are brief and have extra impact when considering that this sort of conduct does not occur often. Seeing these people work away at all hours like a respectable, normal human being endears these characters to us and makes their victory all the more deserved as we have seen the work that he have put into it.

The performances of Stanley Tucci and Billy Crudup in supporting roles as a cantankerous but honorable lawyer and a slick but also surprisingly well-meaning lawyer respectively are standouts. The entire cast is solid and their understated, workmanlike performances fit the tone of the film as a whole as if Glenn Close had been cast in McAdams' role, although she is brilliant, she wouldn't have jelled with the rest of the film. 

The only criticisms that I would have of the film is that it didn't ever convince me that it was more than just very good. Holding the Best Picture distinction meant that I had high expectations for the film and I never felt as though this was one of the greatest films of the decade or even the year. The cinematography also doesn't help as the film has a washed out color palette and the scenery never looks particularly special. I just wanted more in many places and I didn't get it therefore I can't call it a perfect film but it's definitely the best of the films nominated for Best Picture in 2015.
Spotlight is a movie about a team inside The Boston Globe, called Spotlight. They investigate stories and work confidential. When a new editor start the work for the Globe, Spotlight is made to investigate the Geoghan case, which is about a priest that molested children. Once Spotlight starts working on the case they find out about more and more priests who did the same thing.

I was blown away by how great the actors were. Mark Ruffelo and Liev Schreiber stood out for me. They really became Mike Rezendes (Mark's character) and Marty Baron (Liev's character) which I find very fascinating. The way they talk, the way their faces move, it's truly amazing. Michael Keaton as Walter Robinson aka Robby is so good as well (what's new). I feel like all the roles Rachel McAdams plays are kind of the same (she played Sacha Pfeiffer in this one), but she was as marvelous as ever. It wasn't only the main character though. Even the actors with smaller roles were so good. I really enjoyed the acting in Spotlight, which obviously makes the movie even better.

I'm so happy this move got oscars because it really deserves it. The movie is a biography and I love watching films like these because most of the time I didn't even know about the story. As I said before, the actors where great, it's an interesting story and I highly enjoyed it.
Watched Spotlight. Wonderful film. The acting was incredible and I loved everyones performance, and it didn't unrealistically embellish anything. Really down to earth. My one gripe is that in its attempts to be realistic it was almost TOO realistic. I dont think there was even one light hearted moment or a second of laughter in the film. In reality, people do laugh or stutter or trip or get awkward for a second or something. Believe me, the actors are so realistic and consumed by their roles unlike anything I've ever seen. However I'm a guy who needs a little stimulation; the monotony made me a tad drowsy. One moment of explicit comedy or humanness would've gone a long way. Nonetheless, the ending scene absolved almost everything. You realize you've watched the tedious-but-epic quest that exposed a scandal we all know so much about. And, of course, you get that classic theme of good decisively triumphing over evil and feel good walking away from it. 

