Tight, fast paced story telling and the best cast performance of the year; Spotlight tells the story of the investigative team at the Boston Globe and how they pulled the wool off and exposed one of the most egregious and gruesome conspiracies ever perpetrated. Mark Ruffalo and Liev Schreiber were standouts. Both played roles that were against type, and made choices that absolutely paid off. I was most impressed with director Thomas McCarthy never using a specific priest or member of the clergy to carry the weight of antagonist, but rather playing off the idea that all of society was responsible by either not believing what they were being told, or just not wanting to believe it. The journalists who are investigating this story aren't made out to be heroes either. The movie played out exactly as I expect it probably played out in real life. It was that subtle unease and realism that chilled my bones and made a lasting impression.
