Spotlight (2015) is primarily a piece about investigative journalism that shines because it does not over-sensationalize the journalistic process or the people that write the news. Spotlight focuses on the hard facts and the means by which the news acquires these studies, stories, and profiles. The Spotlight team did a tremendous service to society, and the film Spotlight is a brilliant and engaging testament to excellence in journalism.

Tom McCarthy's film is a crescendo of information, scandal, cover-up, and intrigue into the world of Catholic priests molesting and raping young children. Spotlight puts the investigative team and the priest's victims on the forefront of the fight as well as the lawyers that bravely fought the good fight while no one believed them. The sheer volume of evidence, detail, and research that went into these investigations, cases, and the film Spotlight is staggering to say the least. I was very impressed by the director's sleek presentation, but more so the massive amount of care that went into Spotlight. Spotlight will engage, entertain, and horrify you increasingly as the film goes on, but it is well worth watching.

I have to hand it to whoever cast Spotlight. This film is crammed full of brilliant actors giving it their all. Michael Keaton is phenomenal as the head of Spotlight, trying to find the truth and reckoning with his past. Rachel McAdams is incredible and captivating interviewing numerous victims and their powerful testimonies. Mark Ruffalo is impressive for his Bostonian accent and tireless persistent portrayal of a journalist that had to interview sources and unseal documentation of the cover-up. Lastly, Stanley Tucci is sympathetic and endearing as a lawyer that worked ceaselessly to represent and defend the young victims of these pedophile priests, while he simultaneously worked to unseal the documents that broke the Spotlight story with hard evidence and accounts. I really enjoyed the cast of Spotlight all delivering substantial and subtle performances for Spotlight.

In short, Spotlight very well may be one of the most important and impactful films ever made as we constantly hear about more scandals and pedophiles coming from and within The Catholic Church.
