Everyone needs to watch this movie.
Intriguing and compelling, I'm just utterly speechless after watching this movie. One of the best movie about journalism out there. If not, the best. Period
Spotlight tells the fascinatingly dark true story of an investigatory journalist team working within the Boston Globe in the early 2000s. Renown for their probing, detailed format they are tasked by the paper's new editor to investigate a cover-up scandal - mass child molestation within the Catholic church. The sickening premise of what they uncover escalates far beyond what they could have ever predicted. The journalists on screen and us (the audience) are forced to question: how could a situation that had effected so many been silenced for so long, and furthermore, who is responsible?

What starts as an ensemble cast becomes narratively driven by Mark Ruffalo and Michael Keaton's characters, who stood out and resonated most for me. All the crucial characters come with some form of religious baggage, with backgrounds in catholic school or family patronage. All actors involved handle their roles with respect and balance. This is not a film that focuses on individual character development. It's more of a navigation of the wider journalistic story. In its more than 2 hour runtime, the plot is relentless, with information streaming constantly without pause. 
The issue at the heart of Spotlight's narrative could have very easily been hate-fueled, singlehandedly brandishing blame on the church, or religion in general. But the tone doesn't handle the issue in that way. Instead, by the finale, we discover the deeper context. Others members of the community had contributed to the negligence, including attorneys and the press themselves. When the film ended, I was left with this ambiguous and unsettled feeling. The extent of the abuse is incomprehensible and heartbreaking - and you know that this lengthy cinematic adaptation is only skimming the surface.
Spotlight is a riveting journalistic drama that educates and identifies with large-scale corruption in the not so distant past. It delivers intensity in what is essentially a series of scenes where journalist interview persons-of-interest and take a copious amount of notes on spiral notepads.
Spotlight is a biographical investigation film that is directed by Tom McCarthy and stars Mark Ruffalo, Rachel McAdams, Michael Keaton, Stanley Tucci, and many others. It tells the story about The Boston Globe's team called "Spotlight" who gets a new editor, Marty Baron (Liev Schreiber) who is given the task to investigate a catholic priest who sexually abused children. This leads the team to find out there is more at hand here than what was entially thought. 
  The movie is a difficult one to review. It's hard to explain it without spoiling it. So let me try to do my best. It's shocking to find out about a dark secret within the Catholic church. I don't know how much of this was real but I knew the end result was indeed real. This movie is admirable in so many ways and is indeed engrossing to watch, however, I find myself bored at times feeling something big should happen. It never does.  The movie goes back and forth between  the"Spotlight" team, the lawyers, and the victims. Sometimes I was sitting there feeling disturbed, other times I wanted it to hurry up. I felt mixed about this initially but after the movie was over I felt like it was something that was very deep. 
  The movie shows the "Spotlight" team as people just trying to do their jobs and actually feel concerned about the story that's going on. I like the fact that they don't glorify themselves but we see them for how reporters are. It also really shines a light on how dark the Catholic church can be or any religion for that matter. There is a sense of shame that they feel but they try so hard to cover it up using lawyers as a shield to protect themselves. It is indeed scary to know that they are this powerful and manipulative. I obviously don't think all priests or religions are involved in molestation but the possibility is something to ponder about. 
  The cast was very well assembled. Everyone's performance feels authentic and real. I mean they feel like actual people that I work with. I particularly liked Mark Ruffalo with his accent (It's hard for me to explain what kind that is) that seems to grow on you as the movie goes on. He even had a very emotional scene that made me really feel for the victims as for his reason for being upset.  This had a few nominations for supporting actor and actress and it's easy to see why. 
  This movie had a lot of nominations and acclaim behind it and it is indeed well directed, well acted, and well written. This is clearly a drama movie and I recommend it. The thing is that I couldn't get past its slow pace and its lack of ambition. Like I said before sometimes I felt uninterested and I felt like I wanted it to end already. There was a lot of info searching and running into walls that kept the movie bogged down. At the ending, I didn't feel the sense of closure or the bang that it should have had. After all the build up I feel like it deserved something more at the end. Post credits it tells you what happens and it's a bit shocking but still, they could have done a better job.
Well made and engaging.
Let me just gag out my minor complaint, before giving this the inevitable good rating: In this generation of television drama being on par with, sometimes topping, cinematic drama, cinema has become much more comfortable in tossing many names of barely seen characters casually, as if we can follow the happenings as quickly as the highly involved characters. Spotlight is a, er, spotlight example of this. Gag, gag, gag.

Ahem. Yes, this is a winner. Revolved around the uncovery of the magnitude of buried cases of priests molesting children, and how the Catholic Church tried to cover up hundreds upon hundreds of such cases through poorly run rehabilitation centers and bribery towards prosecutors, Spotlight is ripe for Oscar-baiting drama and performances. Director and co-screenwriter Tom McCarthy does tailor certain scenes for such, especially for Mark Ruffalo; I could never tell when his character's disgust and impatience were going to scream over his professional exterior, but every time affected me. However, McCarthy also proves he has a strong understanding of both the motives and the mistakes of some of our greatest journalists. Journalism is not simply a tool; it is a responsibility.
"If it takes a village to raise a child, it takes a village to abuse one."

First things first, I understand that this review is pretty damn late. But what can I say? Just hadn't thought of watching this film until today. Don't know why.

Let me start off with the positives. Spotlight is a pretty great movie. There are some truly golden moments. Mark Ruffalo. Holy motherfucking shit that guy can act!!!! The guy exudes with hard-working passion that adds a lot to this character. Everyone did a fantastic job at acting, top marks to Stanley Tucci and Rachel Mccadams. Michael Keaton was good, but nothing too poignant.

I don't know if anyone else picked this up on their viewing, but there's a lot of references to candy and other childhood pleasures such as gifts and cake in this film that were presented with such a sickly vibe, it added to the constant cold atmosphere and the shame that resonates not just in each character, but the entirety of Boston at the time.

You can tell that the build up was going to be the release of the paper exposing these priests, but what really fascinates me is the attention to how much legal mumbo jumbo you need to process before getting to an appropriate stage in which 1. The Church won't destroy you and 2. Anyone will care. And this doesn't just come from long hours and neglecting love ones, there is a whole meaty segment on these victims who were portrayed beautifully. You felt like the actors had been through genuine trauma.

So what's not to like? The film is a drama, but the balancing of all the workers at 'Spotlight' meant that only Mark Ruffalo was given any platform to express himself. That was a little disappointing. The pacing in this film is drearily slow. The literal opposite of 'Time flies when you're having fun!'.

Nonetheless, Spotlight I recommend you check out (Although the majority of you already have I can assume. It is a cold film about the long complicated road of 'doing the right thing'.

