This is a tough one, folks. By all accounts, this should be a great film. The casting is solid, the story is well directed, the premise is a compelling one, and the respect for the events it was based on is very admirable. Unfortunately, what it achieves in attention to detail and realism it loses in any creative spark. There was no narrative thrust; just scenes playing out in a particular order without any true emotion guiding them. This can potentially alienate the viewers as they won't have anyone to relate to and follow throughout the movie. The only actor who truly stands out here, and whom audiences may find relatable, is Mark Ruffalo as Michael Rezendes, who brings a much needed passion to the role. On one hand, perhaps if the other reporters were better defined characters or if the individual victims were given more attention, there'd be some emotional crutch to latch onto. On the other hand, this could have come across as focusing too on the wrong people with the reporters or becoming too exploitive with the victims. This is not a bad film by any means. However, there's certainly a missed opportunity here and at over two hours, viewers will certainly feel its length.
