Score: 9.5/10
Spotlight is the kind of brutally honest film that truly shows the best that the medium has to offer. This is not a visually impressive film that thinks it has to rely on camera tricks or visual effects to complement its story. This is not a film that has to rely on overly sentimental moments to convey this story. Outside of some very specific scenes, this is not a film that finds a need to devolve into explosive performances to make sure the audience knows a scene is important, and the few times it does, they feel completely natural. Rather than succumbing to these techniques of filmmaking, Tom McCarthy has crafted a subdued slow-burn drama whose unflinching honesty hits you like a punch in the gut. The ensemble here is phenomenal: Michael Keaton, Rachel McAdams, Mark Ruffalo, and Liev Schreiber all give some of the finest performances of their respective careers while being completely subtle, and ultimately transcending the film and truly embodying their characters. It's a shocking, emotional, impactful roller coaster of a film, and certainly deserving of its Best Picture award.
