A stunning testament to the power of journalistic integrity, 2015's best picture winner earned its statue and then some. The movie is a success not for being groundbreaking, but rather telling the very serious story in the simplest way possible, telling like it is. No grimy sound effects, evil music, foreboding flashbacks or other Hollywood motifs to depict the horrors of child molestation. Just the words from the victims, plain and simple. For those unfamiliar with the story, in 2002, The Boston Globe published a shocking article implicating some 90 catholic priests of child molestation, to which the church did nothing. The piece ultimately won The Globe's Spotlight team a Pulitzer for bringing such an unspeakable secret to light. The entire cast is a revelation, particularly Mark Ruffalo and Stanley Tucci. It's not an easy story to either tell or sit through, but the conviction of these reporters and the grip to which they hold their ideals makes the experience riveting rather than grueling. Any fan of potboilers and mysteries (All the President's Men, JFK, Shattered Glass, etc.) shouldn't pass this one up due to its controversial subject matter. It's just too good.
Deserving of best picture.  Second to Star Wars as my favorite of 2015.
