I think this is an example of a "true story" that critics and viewers can't separate from the real-life players. People seem to feel that to gauge this as a stand-alone movie would be to impugn the victims and courageous reporters. Well not to impugn them myself, but as a moviegoer, I found this film to be a real snooze. I already knew it was about the reporters who investigated and exposed the scandal; I lived through that fifteen years ago. So I assumed that to be of full-length feature film significance, there was more to the story. There isn't. I kept waiting for some intrigue: overcoming major obstacles, bribes, vilification, threats; personal faith conflicts, parents who would disown them, spouses who would disavow them. There is none of that. In fact the personal lives of the main characters are barely acknowledged. One character wears a wedding ring but no spouse is ever mentioned. One character is mentioned to be separated from his wife but that's about it. All readily admit in one anticlimactic scene that they were all basically raised Catholic, don't attend church anymore, and meh. Among the lot of them, one is shown to have a nana who will likely be upset when the scandal breaks, and in the end, she asks her granddaughter to-wait for it-bring her a drink of water. Even the victims are downplayed. In one scene we see a victim initially being interviewed, cut to a scene where we are told-told, not shown-that he broke down ten minutes in and couldn't stop crying. You know that scene where Mark Ruffalo's character goes on a tirade about how they "knew, and they didn't do anything"? Yeah, you know it because it was in every commercial, every awards ceremony clip. Because it's about the only dramatic scene in the whole movie. Yes, the real story is of real intrigue. The movie? Not so much.
Spotlight (2015, USA) gained the recent Oscars spotlight after winning the Best Film. Brave and compelling, Spotlight exposed the systematic and systemic sexual abuse of the Roman Catholic Church clergy narrated from the investigative journalism standpoint. Intelligent and alarming, Spotlight features a solid ensemble to complement the aesthetically fluid direction. A you-have-to-see-this 10.
Amazing. Beyond the humanity of all the characters, shows the true need for a serious investigative newspaper force in this country (as opposed to what passes for truth on the Internet 99.999% of the time.)

Ruffalo's as amazing as he always is.
You can spot an Oscar worthy film from a distance. Spotlight is a brilliantly made film on one of the lesser known but horrifying acts done in the name of religion through the perspective of the journalists who uncovered those to bring it to public attention. There are no superheroes, big explosions or surprising twists but it is a film made with meticulous attention and in a way to keep you hooked to your seat despite the absence of popcorn thrills. Supported by a solid cast comprising of Keaton, McAdams, Ruffalo and Liev Schreiber Spotlight in an extremely nuanced and methodical way portrays one of the biggest cover ups behind the veil of the Catholic Church and religion as a whole. It is a story that needs to be known.
