Oscar mais que merecido.
Spotlight is an expertly written, meticulously directed, beautifully acted and brilliantly edited piece of cinema. Tom McCarthy has done a tremendous job at bringing this heartbreaking story to life. He manages to stay as true to the real life source as much as possible and he doesn't dramatize the story. He didn't need to and I'm so glad he didn't attempt it. McCarthy doesn't sanitize this story either, he tells the audience exactly how it is. Right from the get go, he has you glued to your seat, and he makes you leave it speechless.

The production design team have done a brilliant job at re-creating the Boston Globe, where the Spotlight team worked. Every set piece looked incredibly authentic. The film was also edited brilliantly. There isn't a dull moment in this film, every single scene keeps the film moving forward at fast pace.

The performances really enhanced the film, and I truly don't think it could have been made with out this incredible cast. If the actors hadn't gone to such great lengths at portraying these real life people, I think it would have really affected the telling of this dark true life story. It could have felt very sloppy and very insulting. Instead we got brilliant performances, that felt tremendously authentic. Michael Keaton adds another stellar performance to his resume, just after his brilliant performance in Birdman. It's definitely exciting to see his career revitalised. He is joined by great performances by Rachel McAdams, Liev Schreiber, John Slattery, Brian d'Arcy James and Stanley Tucci. However the most notable performance for me was Mark Ruffalo. He truly blew me away. From start to finish he was just incredible. I truly believed his performance. You could tell he really cared about the subject matter and doing it right. I mean the guy asked his real life counterpart if he could watch him yell at someone, just so he could really bring him to life in this film.

Overall, Spotlight is highly informative and an incredibly important piece of cinema. Not only is it beautifully created and tremendously captivating, it's an important story that needed to be told. This happened and continues to happen, and the Church still tries to hide it. The film manages to work so well, purely from its amazing script and brilliant performances, without dramatizing a single thing. It's a brilliantly honest look at one of the darkest stories to emerge from the 21st Century, and it is without a doubt one of the strongest films from 2015, and will most deservedly win Oscars. It's a definite must watch, however it will leave you speechless over the dark subject matter.
I have no words for this movie, is beautiful, is perfect. I was caught from the beginning.
Certainly worthy of the Best Picture Oscar nod, Spotlight's great story and acting make it fun from start to finish.
If you haven't seen this, you should.
Really great film about an interesting topic and brought to life by superb performances from the well chosen cast. It is a highly under rated, and very worthy, film that wears its heart on its sleeve.
