Two words "left field" bravo Tom McCarthy for directing a fantastic film. In addition this is the second film in a row Michael Keaton has stated in which has won best picture which in my opinion is better than winning in the actual category of best actor(not to take away from Leo's Oscar winning performance). This makes Keaton the most valuable actor in Hollywood because for the second year in a row a film he stared in has been "spotlighted" (lol) as the best picture.
Though this review comes a day late and a dollar short of Spotlight's impressive win at the Oscar's for picture of the year, better late than never perfectly describes the journey of this incredible story over a near decade's worth of waiting.

For me, Spotlight was not the film of the year.  It does, however, have the best ensemble bar none.  Keaton, Slattery, Ruffalo, McAdams, Schreiber, James and Tucci rise to the occasion of the source material to not only delivery a tension-based thriller, but a successful, fact-driven adventure that ultimately concludes with a satisfying fist pump so to speak.  While Ruffalo may have been given the nod for best lead actor in the film, it's tough to see him take that home with such a well-rounded cast occupying the same amount of screen time as everyone else.  This wasn't just a Dustin Hoffman/Robert Redford kind of duo.  It was a team effort all the way, and you get a great sense of just how important one journalist was to the other's work.

The material is tough.  The movie throws all the punches it needs to in order to make the audience understand just how heinous these acts were for the the system.  It never glorifies the villain here.  We only briefly get to meet the Cardinal and his disciples, and instead we focus on the journalists who put in the time and hard work necessary to unearth these stories. 

However, the best point to note for director Tom McCarthy is he never idolizes or glorifies any of our heroes.  It's right back to work at the end for these characters who neither need the adulation or seek it.

So while Spotlight should be praised for its delicate handling of the source material, some might actually say it doesn't go far enough.   The text at the end of the movie summarizing everything we watched over the course of two hours doesn't hit as hard as seeing the actors portray it.  But then again, maybe their job was hypothetically completed once the world saw the story on that fateful morning.
Deeply engaging and emotional exploration of a very sensitive, real life issue of sexual abuse and corruption from the very people we turn to for protection, church and state. Rich performances from Mark Ruffalo whose passion as an investigative reporter fires through the challenges to tell the sordid story. I had goose bumps at many points of this film and was emotionally connected to the storyline. Michael Keaton also delivers a strong performance. Amazing film. BEST PICTURE WINNER well deserved.
Not unwatchable, but--and this sinks in as you leave the theater--just awful. Myriads of "characters" all trying to add intrigue and drama to proceedings that have no drama, even though the underlying story is dramatic. People talking in offices. Reporters running through hallways. They could have tried to make it as compelling as JFK. There's a scene in JKF with people sitting at a restaurant table with eerie music and eerie lighting and a sense of foreboding. None of that here, probably on purpose. Very low-key. They were trying to be subtle. Maybe this got the Oscar because the voters wanted to deflect attention from the other issue confronting the Academy this year..
