Solid 70's style newsroom piece that shows you can keep an audience interested for two hours with just the basics
Great movie, great cast, great acting, really good!
Spotlight tells the terrifying true story about a scandal in the Catholic Church from 2001. With an immensely talented performance from Mark Ruffalo, Michael Keaton, and the supporting cast, the film becomes immersive and intense without any violence or effects. With the film taking place in mostly closed spaces, the story is able to be told in a claustrophobic and tense environment, which gives the characters and the audience a feeling of having their backs against the wall. The story may not be simple enough for the casual viewer, but it does provide enough intelligent storytelling and compelling character interaction for the target audience and is a worthy contender for the Oscars.
Took a disturbing subject matter and portrayed it with an honest and interesting way.
Restrained and deeply unsettling, the magnificently crafted and perfectly cast "Spotlight" handles a disturbing topic with respect and finesse, resulting in a exceptional drama that truly honors its real life subjects.
This is kind of a snore if you were paying attention to the story in 2002. Having known of priest abuses from friends as early as 1992, this movie does a good job explaining the "why" behind the systematic brainwashing and justifications of the Catholic Church and its "rationale". But the film isn't terribly emotional or interesting unless you are a reporter and get into the details of reporting. If is new to you it is probably a good movie to see.
Spotlight is an excellent film. 
The dialogue was very well done because it was really well paced and realistic. It felt like a normal person could have actually been saying the lines - and in some instances maybe they were lifted from real life - which was really powerful. It also made events more shocking (the possibly brain-addled priest that calmly confessed on his front porch to having molested young boys), more emotional (when Mark had his outburst, saying that they needed to publish the story right away so it wouldn't get taken by somebody else and messed up) and more brutally, brutally, memorable (any one of the stories of being molested or raped by victims). 
Part of the power of a film like this is that it is a true story and that realism makes it more affecting because while the drama is playing out you also know, as a viewer, that it actually happened. Spotlight's job was to not break that spell and to keep the film as true to reality as possible. Everything about the costumes and the lighting and set design felt very realistic, not to fashionable or favorable. 
Even though it is a form of film (the big cover-up, the feverish investigating, the breaking news story!) that has been done very often and with a lot of success, this still felt fresh and graceful because of its attention to detail and realism.
Superb movie - blew my moderate expectations away. A good-old-fashioned thriller with a collectively wonderful performance by the cast. Unmissable.
I had really hoped that "Spotlight" would live up to the hype of 6 Oscar nominations and its status as the front runner for Best Picture.  It did not.  Expectations aside, I found this film to be interesting and well-done but not at the same level of Oscar contenders like "The Revenant," "Room," and "The Martian."  The only nomination that I would have given to this film is to Tom McCarthy for his screenplay and its treatment of this sensitive subject matter.  The statistics are shocking and the stories of the victims are sad but the film never seems like an attack on the church.  The use of strong sexual language is limited to the first half of the movie, serving as a reference point that we can remember throughout the story without having to hear those words over and over again.  I think that the shock of hearing some of those terms is necessary to grasp the levity of the allegations but I appreciate that the script didn't continually hit us over the head with graphic sexual explanations.  The film focuses on exploring investigative journalism instead of pushing a hidden agenda, and it is impressive that a story about new research could be so riveting.  The acting is above average, especially the Boston accents, but I disagree with the Oscar nominations of Rachel McAdams and Mark Ruffalo in the Supporting categories.  In fact, I enjoyed the acting of Stanley Tucci, Michael Keaton, and John Slattery more than either of them.  Ruffalo gets to shine in one emotional scene but his acting throughout the rest of the film is average when compared by this year's performances by Steve Carrell and Idris Elba.  I'm not even sure what stood out about McAdams' performance to bring her so much acclaim.  Outside of the acting, the atmosphere and sense of authenticity adds to the realism of the story.  It was appropriate to film on location at The Boston Globe where the Spotlight team's findings transpired.  "Spotlight" is a very good movie that handles sensitive events in a creative, informative, and nearly unoffensive way.  Just prepare yourself for two hours of depression and a film that may fall below your expectations for an Oscar contender.
