Investigative reporting isn't interesting day to day. It's mostly busy work, tracking down leads, taking notes, and interviewing people. Films about these investigations amp up the thrill, show reporters' conviction, especially when they crack a case open and go on to challenge an entire system. The best film ever made on this subject is of course "All the President's Men" which covered the Nixon Watergate scandal. There's espionage, drama, abrupt tension, and serious thrill. Hand in hand with that classic is this Oscar nominated gem, "Spotlight." Just as serious an issue drives this film, which is the true story of the Boston Globe's Spotlight team uncovering a sex abuse scandal in the Catholic Church. 

