Great film on an amazing story. Can be tough for films to create intrigue with a journalism story. Spotlight did it better than I've ever seen it done. Fantastic cast!
This is easily the best journalism movie to date. A based-on-a-true-story movie about the Catholic Church cover-up scandal that intensely examines the tragedy on both sides of the coin - "Spotlight" is a very  palpable, very human film that tastefully retells this appalling story that is still fresh in most people's minds, and what a perfect cast to do so! The casting here could not be better: Mark Ruffalo's best screen performance to date, Michael Keaton (fresh off the heels of his tour de force performance in "Bridman") in one of his most complex roles, Rachel McAdams totally making up for 2015's "Aloha" in a much more mature role, Liev Schreiber and Stanley Tucci own every scene they're in - in short, these actors handle their roles with a faultless amount of subtlety that perfectly pairs with the delicate direction masterfully handled by director Tom McCarthy. This more than makes up for McCarthy's other 2015 film - the Adam Sandler mess "The Cobbler". In fact, after watching both it's almost impossible to tell these were directed by the same person. One of 2015's greatest cinematic achievements, "Spotlight" is an intense, powerful examination of both the church and the journalism team who exposed them against all odds that never devolves into a "let's-bash-the-catholic-church" movie that less apt directors very well could have made it out to be. Fascinating, absorbing film - nearly flawless.
Essential contemporary drama circles and centers on holy threads without exploitation of the audience or real life players.  Produces the holy trinity of movies: excellent writing, direction, and acting.
