I just finished watching Spotlight and I am shaking.  I am not exactly sure why, I'm overwhelmed on so many levels - I am angry, I am sad, I am terrified, I am in awe of the art of storytelling in this movie, I am full of admiration for the morality that finally came through to reveal these crimes, and I am embarrassed by the evil that exists in this world perpetrated by selfish heinous humans against our most vulnerable. This movie is one of those movies that will never leave you, it gets in your psyche and colours the world differently - good and bad. 
Mark Ruffalo is fast becoming my favorite actor; he delivers this role with such depth that you barely notice his at-first obvious blatant lack of social skills as the movie progresses.  You start to see a deeper struggle, possibly a long hidden secret, you are transfixed by him, he tears your heart out when he finally explodes. Yet it's all subtle and brilliant.
It's  a difficult movie to watch, not because of vulgar scenes of gross indecencies portrayed but because our mind goes there, whether you want to or not, it plays out in the worst ways in your head. It shows the ugliness without showing one gratuitous act of deprivation. See it, please, and maybe we can all learn to be more accountable to hard truths.
One of the best movies of 2015
Good acting, unbelievable that it was a true story.
Rightly regarded as one of the finest films of 2015, Spotlight is an intelligent and compelling look at one of the biggest deceptions of the 21st century. A witty and often biting script cuts to the core of investigative journalism and the true effects of systemic abuse, and an impeccable cast brings the characters to life. Every actor is on top form, and none more so than Mark Ruffalo. So fantastic as the troubled Hulk in the Avengers, here we seem him truly transforming into a bright, ambitious, resourceful but also emotionally driven and occasionally overzealous reporter. The way he moves, speaks and even his facial expressions, everything he does convinces you that he is 100% invested in this role.
This is certainly a very wordy movie, with much being said and analysed, and often at a rapid pace. But it works because the story is constantly being advanced and new developments are always being made. Issues such as the deep dependence on the Church and the harmful consequences that such a blind faith can have make up the backbone of the story, but the movie never makes the mistake of being a cheap finger poke at religion, fully acknowledging that the issue is the abuse of power employed by those within its ranks, and not the institution itself, that causes the damage. The facts the movie reveals are truly shocking, and its final moments will leave you stunned. Spotlight is a solid piece of cinema, rooted in fact and flowering in the minds of its viewers.
