Spotlight is exactly the kind of movie that critics love and audiences may find a little boring. The story, obviously, is one that needed to be told.  The acting ensemble all capably perform.  However, even though the stakes were high and the subject matter is certainly infuriating, I still felt a sense of detachment, perhaps because the protagonists are reporters with no connection to their story.  In a way, I felt like I was reading about a story more than experiencing it, which is what I usually expect from a film.
Granted I haven't seen all of the nominated movies...but I can't see many recent films being as carefully constructed as Spotlight (tho Brooklyn is way good as well). The tireless journalism and teamwork it took to bring this story to fruition is the kind of writing that inspired me to major in journalism. Pity most papers don't have the resources to devote to this type of in depth reporting.
[Original version that I typed on 11/22/15 but forgot to post on RT] 
Imagine dusting/digging the ground and finding a bit of a fossil. You're all excited, you think you have it all figured out and then you realize that the fossil is part of a limb, which is a part of a whole animal that you'd never have guessed to uncover. In a way, that's kind of what "Spotlight" is about. You have that guy who played Cotton from "Scream" become the boss of Michael Keaton's journalism team for the Boston Globe (featuring the Hulk, I mean, Mark Ruffalo) and decides that the team should pick up [report on] a case about a priest. Well, since this is based on true events, I think I'm safe to say that one thing leads to another--Ruffalo and the others meet up with abuse victims, crooked lawyers, clergy members, etc--and the story picks up like a wildfire after the film's first act. The team is now basically in conflict in the church as their list of suspected dirty priests blows up from one to eighty seven. The Catholic Church in this movie gets, like, a "mafia-esque" treatment with talks about under-the-rug settlement cases, public legal documents being removed, the church not firing bad priests and moving them to different parishes instead, and how the Church "goes after" people who try to make them look bad. And there's often shots where characters might be discussing traumatic past experiences or something and the camera pans out a bit, and what's in the background? A church, I mean, the filmmakers definitely do a remarkable job at giving the church this looming presence like "they're down the street, they're your next door neighbors, they're everywhere." The film ends with a text that the team found about 1,000 victims and named over 200 priests (JUST in Boston) who had molested kids, and then there's a list of cities in the U.S and other countries where the clergy have abused children. That's important to know because people tend to forget the victims and that's just not okay. In fact, that might even be why the problem persists today, I haven't looked into the actual statistics but Wikipedia says that the number is declining. I have my doubts, I think the Church is still covering for their members. The Boston Globe printed this story in 2002 (or so they say in the film). These accusations go back who knows how further back AND since then, a 2014 article by the BBC said that the U.N accused the Vatican of "systematically adopting policies that allowed priests to sexually abuse thousands of children." The Church (the hierarchy or what have you) has a history of not reporting these crimes, they did nothing for decades. These are facts. Not my biased opinion. And they're startling. They are startling in the movie and they're even scarier when you think about the real world issue--how long it's persisted, how many victims are out there, and that it still happens. These scandals are worldwide, they go beyond just the Catholic Church (other Christian denominations and other religions have seen their fair share of 'the nasty'), and....well, it's all part of "the plan," right? There was this one lady behind me, or a few seats behind me, she had a very strong reaction to the film, she was talking a lot, and when the movie ended she asked, "what would Jesus do?" The answer is simple: God/Jesus/[insert any deity that is claimed to be all loving and all knowing] wouldn't have let it happen AND he wouldn't let it continue, but, he did and he does. And all that that implies. Anyways, back to the movie: the performances are good (the actors who played the adult victims were really good), it starts a bit slow but goes from zero to sixty after the half hour mark or so, Mark Ruffalo owns this one scene where his character expresses his frustrations, and there were some tense-y scenes moments that I really liked. 
P.S Yes, I was raised catholic. No, I am not catholic any more nor will I ever be. The funny thing is that I watched a documentary and that was when I started to not believe or whatever. To be frank, I'm not even sure why the documentary had that particular effect on me--it's clear to me, at least now, that it was full of bullshit. Fun fact: I actually did consider becoming a muslim for a very, very short period of time. Yeah, I was like that Pi kid from "Life of Pi"--searching for God or whatever. I did end up getting a sign from the divine, though. This is true, I swear on my life, I watched Godzilla last year and I converted right away. Godzilla watches over me; he's my lord and savior. He actually saves people, sure, he might stomp through a city, but it's the greater good that counts. Allah/God/and all them seem more content with playing games and "testing" folks, man, G-zilla don't play around 'cuz he ain't no Joke.
