Great story. Gripping stuff. Really enjoyed this film.
"Spotlight" tells the true story of the 2001 investigation by the Boston Globe into the Catholic Church's child molestation scandal. ("Spotlight" is the name of the Globe's investigative reporting team.) 

The story begins with Marty Baron (Liev Shreiber) taking over as the Globe's new editor.  At the time, there was a minor case alleging that an archbishop named Cardinal Law was engaged in a cover-up in which he shuffled priests accused of pedophilia from parish to parish while continuing to allow them to work with children. While such rumblings were nothing new, the paper had never really pursued them in deference to Boston's powerful Catholic Church. But Baron, being a Jewish outsider, instructs the team to launch an all-out investigation. 

Normally I'm not a big docudrama fan but this movie feels a lot more "docu" than drama. I had a little bit of a hard time keeping all of the names straight and got tripped up just about every time someone mentioned Cardinal Law, thinking it was some sort of legal term. 

Though the legal maneuverings involving sealed documents are somewhat interesting, the movie is at its best when the victims tell their stories. Mark Ruffalo is particularly good as one of the reporters and Rachel McAdams is pretty convincing as well. The beauty of this film is that despite being jam-packed with big name Hollywood stars, all of the performances are all low-key and believable.

This is one of those rare times when walking into the theater with low expectations really paid off for me.  "Spotlight" is both educational and engrossing, as any good documentary should be. The fact that it's actually a drama makes this quite a feat.
