A testament to the power of simply great storytelling. Spotlight doesn't try to reinvent the wheel. It's not flashy, subversive, meta, or overly-artistic. In some ways (such as cinematography) it's almost by-the-numbers. Even the music by Howard Shore is incredibly restrained. The movie rests on the script and the actors performances, everything from the cinematography, editing, and music take a back seat to and point all our attention to the acting and story and boy, does this cast deliver. 

It's a reminder of the simplicity of just good storytelling. The script is fantastic, handling delicately an already delicate situation, giving a voice to victims, never becoming vulgar, or even glamorizing the protagonists completely. 

A solid, excellent film.
