Tom McCarthy's awards season bio-drama tells a taxing tale which often surprises, but never stuns.
Considering its subject matter, this account of investigative journalism into paedophilia in the Catholic Church is wholly anti-sensationalist in both storytelling and style - and sometimes all the better for it.
McCarthy's calm, documentary-like feature isn't afraid to pull its viewers along slowly and reveal its secrets softly, but the distance it keeps from its key characters tends to leave us bemused when they breakdown at random in sporadic nods to Academy voters.
Worse still, Spotlight suffers from the ironic sensibility that - much like the characters it portrays - the story it is trying to tell is far greater than the film's ability and capacity to actually tell it.
Spotlight is a cold biopic with a distinct lack of character and a distinct abundance of "Hey, Academy members - look at me!"
