http://cineptimoarte.blogspot.mx/
Anchored by its excellent lead performances, "Spotlight" is a worthy new addition to the pantheon of Journalism Thrillers (as exemplified by the still unmatched "All the President's Men").  The screenplay and direction are taut and well paced, creating the opportunity for some truly engaging performances from Mark Ruffalo, Michael Keaton and supporting players Billy Crudup, Stanly Tucci and Liev Schreiber.  Ruffalo's intense, tweaky portrayal of journalist Mike Rezendes is a compelling joy.  The wonderful Rachel McAdams, so surprising in the messy second season of "True Detective", is somewhat under-utilised, and the score is pedestrian.  Still, "Spotlight", like many well made films, transcends its minor flaws to tell a very dark, sad and disturbing story in an entertaining and riveting manner.  It's a rare example of no "bells and whistles" film making, allowing its story and performances to intrigue the audience.
