Overrated - slow and dull
For a while the film seems well made but not in any way extraordinary or special. I don't know how to accurately describe the feeling, but I guess it would be along the lines of "well that was a movie". However the longer the film goes on, the more engaging it gets, and about halfway through I was in it with the last half hour or so being pretty intense. The highlights of the film are one scene in particular where Mark Ruffalo gets to let it all out, and the last ten minutes or so of the film. I admit the ending felt a bit abrupt because I guess a part of me wanted to feast on the aftermath which isn't shown, but with how great a moment the ending is, I can totally understand ending the movie there, because you can't really ask for a better scene to end on. More than anything though I'm glad this film was made because making this story a part of popular culture will help it to not be forgotten which it shouldn't be because it's too important to forget. It's one of the most upsetting examples out there of how established institutions with too much power can and do get away with murder when they become too ingrained in the fabric of society and indoctrinate people to be loyal to them to the point where no one will ever challenge them again.

