The Best Picture frontrunner, Spotlight, handled the wrongdoings of the Catholic Church in Boston and beyond to near-perfection. It insists on telling the facts as they stood, treats victims with sensitivity and avoids over-dramatisation. This approach naturally leads to the conclusion that a documentary would have sufficed, as it is the story and not the journalism or lawyer chit chat that keeps the film interesting. Of course, an all-star cast would have outvoted that idea for money and awards. That being said, the cast do work well together, but there is certainly less dramatic work for them here than in The Big Short.
