Spotlight tells a harrowing story, made all the more harrowing by the fact that it is as close to the truth as we can believe. The harrowing story of how a religion was used as a prop in one of the worst things to happen in this world's history, and the knocking down of those walls by some humble newspaper journalists. 


Watching Spotlight before its Best Picture Academy Award. I found myself both infused, yet off the boil. It isn't that this film is bad. That couldn't be much further from the truth. The main problem here is that it is packed to the rafters with dialogue. It does hold the interest of the viewer, but watching this, I can only think of how much this perhaps should have been a book rather than a film. Having said that, as a film this is high-quality cinema, well put together and pure solid gold. Shining a spotlight over one of the darkest things imaginable. This film is not particularly original in its format, but it is in the way it goes about telling you its story. You could just listen to this and be equally as happy and I don't know what I should think about that. I sat in the chair and was completely sucked into this film, and as I left the cinema, I felt as though I had been shocked ("shocked". The age of the understatement). Shocked more by the true story rather than the actual film. Although, as I thought about this film more and more; I became aware that I liked this film a lot more than I first thought. If the story is shocking, the film is putting that story in coherent form and harnessing that shock. The film plays as a narration of the finding of evidence and the actual confrontations in this film are few and far between; I can only think of one or two solid confrontations that actually made me recoil. The steady growth of this film makes it incredible. Far from boring, but for some reason slightly unfulfilling. Maybe the subject matter is to blame for that. Maybe I just need to watch this again. I feel as though I am understating this film, but the truth is, I haven't actually made my mind up on this one.

You'd be forgiven for watching this film just based on the cast. It is a top class cast and not one member of this cast steps one foot wrong here, and when they do; they had to. The cast play against an invisible villain and work off of each other so well that you never even once begin to question anything. See yourself in these character's and recognize some of humanities flaws. No heroes, just humans. Working shock and intrigue into a tight, but somehow messy, yet all the more satisfying and saddening bundle. Really, the single members of this cast cannot be mentioned on their own. For each of the cast members plays as well as the next. A true ensemble of true actors, playing true characters, in a true film. Perfection on the performance front. You won't even find yourself thinking about it, and that is a high compliment for such a film that hones on the truly horrific details of the story-line and paying off when needed. I would have loved to see more back and forth between these performers though. As mentioned before, the confrontations here are few and far between and could have given the film a different fold to slip down.

Spotlight is perfection on all levels, but the fact it has been put on screen. Sometimes, some things just work better on the page. Prepare for a bumpy ride. Prepare to be disgusted. Prepare to feel... As long as a film can make you do that, then it has worked on some level. Spotlight, I salute you. You had me on the edge of my seat, whilst burying me inside of it. I hope I haven't buried you six feet under in this review. 

The best works have their smallest mistakes on view for us to talk down.
