Outstanding movie about the Boston Globe's successful exposing of the Catholic Church priest scandal.
The business-as-usual approach by its lead characters when dealing with a very sensitive subject avoiding to be melodramatic (few occasions and that's just about apt) and sensational is in itself an achievement. The casting did help too.
It is impossible not to compare Spotlight with All the President's Men. Alan J. Pakula's film is the Citizen Kane of investigative films (and not to mention one of my personal favourites of all time). Tom McCarthy's Spotlight is a worthy companion and takes on an even bigger subject matter, but ultimately doesn't have the flair of All the President's Men. The direction of Spotlight is so understated that it doesn't even feel like there is a director at all. But what it lacks in direction it makes up for in the performances. Mark Ruffalo is the one who has gotten all of the attention, mainly because he is the only member of the cast with a showy role. For me, the scene where Ruffalo really lets loose is probably one of the weakest parts of the film, standing out like where every other scene is understated and quiet. It is actually Michael Keaton and Liev Schreiber who I thought really shone here. Schreiber in particular reminded me of Gary Oldman in Tinker Tailor Soldier Spy in just how restrained his performance was
