I just saw this movie after experiencing something traumatic. There were only 10 tickets sold for Spotlight and Norm of the North tickets were out of sale, since Norm of the North will win best animated feature this year...
Anyways Spotlight is directed Tom McCarthy and stars Michael Keaton, Mark Ruffalo, Rachel McAdams and Liev Schreiber. This film is about the Boston sexual abuse scandal and how the catholic church was involved, and the journalists setting to uncover the story. The acting in this movie is superb. The cast is amazing, but Mark Ruffalo steals this movie. His character is very likable, he is witty and funny. It's incredible that the actors blend with their characters, as I watched the movie I didn't think that Michael Keaton was on the screen, but that Robby was the man I was seeing. The movie does a great job on engaging us in the topic, and shocking us moment after moment, as we start to realize the seriousness and scope of this problem. The dialogue is great, since we actually feel pity for the victims of this horrible scandal. It really doesn't try to idolize the journalists, but depict it as it actually is, a group of journalists trying to uncover a story that will help the Boston Globe gain fame and followers, but it still lightens up the good in the journalists especially Ruffalo's character. This movie is amazing, and that is why without a doubt, I give it an A.
