Indianapolis, my home sweet home, isn't exactly known for it's large Catholic presence, so I'm not sure how big a splash the story made in 2001. The story now is making a splash because of how well director Tom McCarthy crafted the journalistic aspect into a film with a great actors followed by great performances. Spotlight may very well win the Best Picture Oscar, and I'm fine with it. The plot was very compelling, the narrative moved along a suspenseful pace that a newspaper doesn't always do, and the acting is what made the film.
It plods through its matrix in an efficient if not inspired manner. As a press procedural it boasts few outstanding features except for Keaton's teeth and Ruffalo's dodgy eye. Child abuse and the Catholic Church is a story so often told that this rather timid re-telling, hardly raises an an eyebrow of concern. Yes there is something rotten in the state of the Vatican but this rather anodyne disinfectant lacks the power or the passion to flush it out.
This is probably one of the more important movies of the year because of the story it tells.
