With a smart script, a continuous atmosphere of apprehension and great performances all around, Spotlight suceeds in every level to deliver a fact-based story about child abuse from priests of the Catholic Church and its ramifications without resorting to idealizations, even though it may seem too conventional for some viewers.
My Favourite to take out Best Picture at The Oscars. Best Picture of The Year.
A proper film about proper journalism, Spotlight is an account of the Boston Globe's investigation into the activities of paedophile catholic priests. What they uncover is a sickening and shocking amount of abuse by predatory priests that was covered up for decades by the upper echelons of the church and the wider establishment. A difficult and harrowing tale, the subject is beautifully handled by director Tom McCarthy. The plot focuses very much on the tight knit investigative "Spotlight" team, who are tasked to work on long running, in-depth stories. This four person team, headed by editor Walter Robinson uncovers the unbelievable scale of the abuse and the lengths people went to in order to hush things up. A strong cast is headed by Michael Keaton who gives one of his finest performances as Robinson. Other members of his team are played by the excellent Mark Ruffalo, Brian d'Arcy James and Rachel McAdams with other key roles taken by the wonderful Stanley Tucci and Liev Scheiber. I really can't praise this deeply moving film highly enough and while it is not an easy viewing, it is one that is very well worthwhile seeing.
Superb acting and an excellent script held my attention throughout - even though the end result was already known.
Spotlight is based on true events and stars Michael Keaton, Rachel McAdams, Mark Ruffalo, John Slattery, Brian d'Arcy James, and Liev Schreiber as employees of the Boston Globe who uncovered the story of Catholic priests molesting children and covering up the evidence with help from high-ranking Cardinals. The film was nominated for six Academy Awards, winning Best Original Screenplay and Best Picture. What else is there to say about a movie with that prestige?

To start, the cast is great. Mark Ruffalo (who was nominated for Best Supporting Actor) really shines. Liev Schreober, playing the editor of the Globe, is the initial driving force that gets the ball rolling. Stanley Tucci delivers a humbling and troubled performance as a lawyer who has defended many victims of this abuse. There isn't a poorly-given performance or an annoying character in this entire movie, which is refreshing.

It's the little things that really carry the load here, however. Howard Shore (Lord of the Rings franchise) composes a beautiful, melodic, and at times haunting score, appropriately accompanying the tone of the film. Speaking of tone, major props to McCarthy! With this story, it would have been easy to approach it in a melodramatic way, but he directs a very respectful film here. The pacing of the movie is also very consistent. My dad said "there was never really a lull," and I agree. The movie just keeps snowballing, getting bigger and more urgent.

Now, I do have a couple tiny nit-picks with this movie. There's a little bit of journalism jargon I didn't understand at first because the words were used in a way that gave no information to their meanings, but it became clearer as time progressed. Hey! Speaking of progressing time, there was really no clear indication about how time passed in this movie. In one scene, they mention how the Spotlight story had been put to the side for six weeks because of 9/11. There was a montage scene later on depicting the further passing of time, but the random jumps felt odd with no explanation.

Folks, this movie won Best Picture for a reason. When you combine a true story with a cast like this, the odds are ever in your favor (remember 12 Years a Slave?) If you enjoy movies based on true events or just good movies in general, go watch Spotlight today (ON NETFLIX!)

Final rating: A-
Based on the incredible true story of how the Boston Globe uncovered the massive scandal of child molestation and cover-up within the local Catholic Archdiocese, Spotlight manages to deliver a fantastic retelling of the story with very well execution, a very intense theme, and a cast of charming and unforgettable characters with an all-star cast to go with it. For years, there have been so many movies about people trying to uncover huge scandals and most of these movies have failed to make themselves likeable, and then suddenly, Spotlight comes in and shows these other movies how a true story is supposed to be retold properly!!! I highly doubt that I will ever see a movie this engaging and enjoyable as Spotlight, but the one thing I know for sure, is that this is definitely one of 2015's best movies ever.
