Esta pel√≠cula acerca de como un diario se atreve a hablar sobre lo que todo el mundo sabe pero niega respecto a los abusos sexuales de los sacerdotes y como la iglesia cat√≥lica con todo su poder oculta la verdad es una pel√≠cula que trasciende m√°s all√° de los premios √ìscar. Adem√°s con una referencia directa a San Luis Potos√≠ nos obliga moralmente a recomendarla. La fe es importante para el mundo pero tambi√©n la verdad.
Spotlight brings to the light the harrowing true story of the sexual abuse that has been going on within the Catholic Church.  Set in the City of Boston, Liev Schreiber plays the newly appointed editor of the Boston Globe newspaper and he sets a team of investigative journalists, known as Spotlight the task of unraveling the decades worth of allegations made against priests in the Boston area over the course of decades and how the church bury said allegation.

Spotlight brings together an ensemble cast including Michael Keaton, Mark Ruffalo, Stanley Tucci and Rachel McAdams in what is riveting thriller.  Unlike The Big Short, one of the other films nominated for Best Pictire, I did not feel alienated despite the complex nature of the story, that's where Spotlights main strength is, in it's storytelling.  Spotlight is a wonderfully constructed movie with all the cast putting in stellar performances without the conceit of other movies that considered Oscar bait.

The characters are well drawn-out and you get a feel for the gravity of the story they are unfolding, however they are not made out to be heroes, they are simply doing their job, a job in an environment where they themselves have been complicit in the atrocities put upon some of the children within the church.  In this film the victims are not forgotten and we get to know in graphic detail what they went through.

Spotlight is a story that needed to be told and it's a brilliantly told one at that.
"It takes a village to raise a child. It takes a village to abuse one too". . . Haunting words spoken from a film that has now put the Catholic church under fire like never before. Back in 2001, the world was shocked in an instant when an evil force took a couple of planes and showed the American culture how delusionally safe we really were. But while the dust and destruction of 9/11 seemingly overshadowed the world, a crack team of investigative journalists from the Boston Globe were planning on shining some light on another evil that had been secretly preying on our people for years. "Spotlight" was the Boston Globe's journalism branch that took this monster on. . . Their mission, to break down the battle tested defensive walls of the Catholic church and expose a protected ring of child molestation that had been going on for how long, nobody knows. With the church's claws in the community and the courts alike, this team would have to stop at nothing to hit their mark. Turn every stone, track down each victim they could find, push the buttons of the powers that be, and show a level of perserverence when it seemed like the world would be against them. What they found in the end was nothing anybody could have fathomed. The shepards do indeed tend to their flocks, but what happens when you find an entire pack of wolves dressed in shepard's clothing???
	I can tell why the church is pissed about this piece of work. If they had a heavy hand in trying to quash the initial story, the now critically acclaimed film depicting their fateful attempt in doing so must pose as a kill shot to their general perception now. And if any of this is true, which many sources are pointing to be the case, it is simply maddening. The level of protection and enablement by a system dedicated to the serving of good, the denial of the public that follows suit, and the lack of accountability sentenced on those found guilty. This film is duely well done and serves as another punch to the gut reminder of how the human race has descended to hell in a hand basket. Directing, acting, and a beautifully ominous score serve as high notes to this wonderfully told scandal. My only qualm comes from the writing and adaptation of the story, which I found lacking in the conflict it was promising. For how threatened this team was for trying to wage war on an enemy they were told would stop at nothing to shut their efforts down, we didn't see much of that backlash as the team seemed to really put things in motion once they connected the dots. We didn't see that "hell hath no fury who poses a threat to the Catholic Church" that we all would expect. For that, the conflict and resolution of the film seemed rather casual and hitting light on points that should be much more emotionally scarring. It was a minor blemish to an otherwise rather beautiful model of one of the ugliest stories to rock our culture these past many years. "Spotlight" shines bright and should finish a close third to The Big Short and The Revenant for best movie of 2015.

GRADE: A-
