A very solid film from the workman McCarthy who does everything to just get out of the way and let a story stand on its own two legs. A film that gets into the legwork of real journalism that is inspiring in its dogged determination and as a light criticism of the death of journalism and the rise of Facebook stories. What else have we missed as newspapers have been slashed and anyone can write an op-ed with no sourcing or attempt at even-handedness and we celebrate it because it validates our opinions?
A group of reporters dig deep into the systemic abuse of children by Catholic Priests which turned out to be a worldwide epidemic that the Catholic Church was well aware of and was deliberately keeping secret, covering up, and ignoring. With about 6% of priests engaged in sexual abuse (with over 400,000 in the world that leaves about 25,000 who hurt children over who knows how many years) they uncover something beyond comprehension. The film fleshes out the characters just enough to give them some dimension, but not enough to take the focus from the overall narrative and turn it into something personal and schmaltzy. Some hard hitting scenes with victims, blame to go around for everyone, solid ensemble acting (Ruffalo stands out, obviously), and some nice musings on the even grander effects of those who are robbed of their faith because of this and you are left with a movie that will leave you full of righteous indignation. Look for it to pull best picture for old Hollywood style (All the President's Men) and true-story of do-gooders.
As a survivor, I cannot thank the cast, crew, producers, and everyone connected with this work enough. It is honest in it's portrayal of the victims and their pain, the degree and depth of cover up, and the desire of some to continue ignoring the issue and others who advocate for those of us who suffered. Thank you for the healing tears, and for your gentle handling of a terrible chapter for many of us.
