My thoughts ran rampant when I first saw Spotlight. On one hand, it¬ís a very good story about uncovering scandal in one of Boston¬ís largest unofficial organizations. On the other, it¬ís a little one-dimensional, uninspiring at times, and preachy. Media members alike love this movie because it¬ís a true recanting of heroic journalistic integrity. It should be noted the cast is highlighted by a great performance by Mark Ruffalo, who has received a Best Supporting Actor nod from the Academy for his rendition of Boston Globe columnist Michael Rezendes. I¬íll give Spotlight the benefit of the doubt¬óafter all, it was better than 90 percent of Hollywood releases this year.
By Ricky Miller
I am rarely left speechless when I go to the movies. 
"Spotlight" was one of the exceptions.  In this based-on-truth story, to see, let alone hear about what happened to young boys,  was reprehensible.  
Michael Keaton headlines as Walter "Robby" Robinson, head of a team of Boston reporters who band together and spend every moment delving into their story.  Other members of the team include Sacha Pfeiffer (Rachel McAdams),  Mike Rezendes (Mark Ruffalo) and Matt Carroll (Brian d'Arcy James).
The team works feverishly every waking moment at the Boston Globe, where they fight to put the story to bed by the end of the day.
As the story moves on and weaves its tableau, the amount of wrongdoings by various members of the clergy is shocking and downright disgusting.  During the team's inquiry into the Catholic Church, it is surmised that more than 70 higher ups within the church were in the wrong. 
On the lighter side of things, Stanley Tucci ("The Hunger Games") is stellar as attorney Mitchell Garabedian.  When his persona is on the screen, one listens to every nuance and bit of dialogue he utters.
Even McAdams' Sacha character mentions she does not join her grandmother anymore at daily mass for the sheer principal of it all.  Because of the events occurring at the church, Sacha feels that even attending mass would be a slap in the face to all of the victims.  
Also integral to the story is Liev Schreiber's  Marty Baron, the Boston Globe's editor-in-chief.  He wants to know the nitty gritty of it all, down to actual concrete proof.
Filling in the blanks of bureaucracy and all-around corruption are Billy Crudup's Eric Macleish, an attorney representing the Archdiocese of Boston, who was integral in part of the cover-up.
Another person fueling the cover up is Paul Guilfoyle's Pete Conley, who tries to shed various church clergy from embarrassment due to their improprieties.
In the end game of things, this hardcore drama will leave you with a feeling of disbelief and amazement on how this cover-up has gone on for so many years.  
In the end game of things, the Boston Globe walked away with multiple Pulitzer prizes for reporting on incidents that occurred in the city and it turns out all over the world.
Grade:  A
