Powerful in the extreme.
Spotlight is a film that takes a close look at the process that the reporters from the Boston Globe went through in order to break the story of a number of Catholic priests molesting children.  I'm always impressed when a film can take a historic event where I know the end result and still keep me captivated from start to finish.  This movie is loaded with sequences that could easily be boring (flipping through books, interviewing lawyers, etc.) and yet I was captivated throughout all of it.  Somehow they managed to continue raising the stakes, and did a superb job of articulating the roadblocks they faced.  While the script and directing deserve a fair amount of credit, I also have to give a lot of praise to the ensemble cast.  Everyone just perfectly nailed their characters (some working with accents or different speech patterns as well) to the point where I felt like I knew them without any of their back-story.  I didn't realize just how much this film was connecting with me until they reached the end of the film and gave some of the aftermath facts.  Suddenly, I was involuntarily weeping.  I think it was just the combination of the victim interviews that the investigators engage in throughout the film, and then their articulation of my own frustration with the entire system.  It all compounded to connect with me in ways I never expected.  I cannot recommend Spotlight enough, it was a great film and one that touches on a scandal that is difficult to face, but one that needed to be addressed.
There's a reason this movie is one of the favourites for Best Picture #oscars
