I've never been to Boston, but I've always thought it a c**t of a city. Not just because of its sickening support of the terrorist murderers of the IRA, or its overly-sentimental dewy-eyed oirish heritage, but because its fans and adherents always seemed the sort of people who are long on arrogance and short on morality, and this film kind of sets the record straight. As one who was at a school loosely linked to similar scandals in the UK, it is important that a decent account is made of these disgusting clerics and their corrupt church. Spotlight is well-meaning and although almost marred by Ruffalo's insufferable scene-chewing performance, makes a decent fist of telling the story but with notable omissions in that we see few survivors and - apart from one jaw-dropping all-to-brief scene - no abusers. But although it rattles along, it doesn't climax and there's nothing here that comes close to All The President's Men, the benchmark by which such a movie has to be set.
A hard-hitting, factual, and emotional ride that doubles as a look into how the field of investigative journalism for print used to work. The Spotlight team (a four person intensive investigative journalist team for The Boston Globe) stumbles upon the conspiracy/cover-up of the century when they investigate a sexual abuse claim involving a catholic priest and discover that this kind of thing has been going on for decades, involves many more priests than originally expected, and it goes all the way up to the top of the Catholic church. This is more of an ensemble film, and our leads do fantastic jobs. Mark Ruffalo (Who slowly boils over into a raw, intense, driven, emotional performance) is Mike Rezendes, Rachel McAdams is Sacha Pfeiffer, Michael Keaton is Walter "Robby" Robinson (the editor and head of the Spotlight team), and Brian d'Arcy James (Who also portrayed Shrek on Broadway. He blends seamlessly into his role here) is Matt Carol. They all shine as our Spotlight team. Liev Schriber as new editor Marty Baron (The man who sets it all into motion by assigning the Spotlight team onto the story), Stanley Tucci as Mitchell Garabedian (A lawyer who had filed some of the first claims of sexual abuse against the catholic church), and John Slattery as Ben Bradley Jr. are fantastic as well. Some of the imagery is a bit haunting (plenty of shots of Catholic churches that loom over both our heroes and suburban houses), and there are a surprising amount of moments where the floor drops out from under you as the true scope and extent of the damage is revealed (A great example is the closing text crawl that left my jaw dropped in horror). Spotlight sheds light on one of the most important news stories of the past several decades, and it is to be commended for tackling it's subject material with passion while still remaining faithful to the truth of the story. Simply put: Spotlight is an incredible film. It's enough to make you mourn the death of print journalism.
excellent account and great performance by mark ruffalo
