Important without being self-important and the cast comports themselves admirably, even though in most cases that means taking a step back and letting the story shine through.  Nonetheless, there's nothing remotely cinematic about it, and the cast of premium cable stars (Slattery, McAdams, Schreiber) just enhances the perception that this only made it to the big screen because one of last year's best actor nominees agreed to take part.  Leaves a couple of intriguing plot threads dangling (like McAdam finding a priest who happily admits to committing child abuse, only for everyone to forget the whole thing within five minutes); that's a problem in a film where the climax is so obvious at the outset.
I loved this movie and was particularly glad that it wasn't (a) preachy, (b) filled with the all too normative Hollywood soup-du-jour agenda, (c) an opportunity to bait and switch the audience so that we were subjected to gratuitous and desensitizing homosexual or pedophile imagery and (d) it wasn't flashy. It was refreshing to watch a story tell itself without over-dramatization. The acting was superb.  

This is not a flashy film, which is part of its beauty. It feels authentic. Despite an article I read criticizing the Boston Globe, I think the movie acknowledged there were missed opportunities along the way. 

I wish there were more films made like this. Thank you!
