Best drama I have seen in a long time.  Easy to follow, fantastic acting, and emotional.  I cannot believe the things that Spotlight uncovered with so many powerful forces against them and the actors in this film really demonstrate the struggles of fighting the church.
Masterpiece of story. Good watch. Mark Ruffalo was outstanding too.
Proof of the virtue of doing something simply, but doing it very well. "Spotlight" does not reinvent the wheel, but it matches a sharp script with a cast that, from top-billed to cameos, is filled with actors who know their business. As a result, there's not really a false note or misstep in the film.

It also excels because it avoids the sort of pitfalls that one would expect from a typical Hollywood film that deals with an Important Sensitive Subject: the righteous indignation is kept to a minimum, and the temptation to "make it personal" for the main characters is likewise moderated. Instead, "Spotlight" makes itself about the work of news reporting, and is refreshingly subtle and nuanced in both its tone and its mise en scene. A superb, "textbook" drama.
fantastic 
I absolutely loved this movie from beginning to end
A story that needs to be told is handled with great care here. The actors greatest strength in this film is how understated and therefore believable their performances were.
An unremarkable looking movie about a remarkable group of people. Spotlight is well made, compelling, and stacked with some of the best working actors out there. Tackling the church sexual abuse scandal of the early 2000s, Spotlight has a barn burner of a story and it knows. The best praise I could give this movie is that it plays like All The President's Men. The film shows the nitty, gritty of investigative journalism and it does so with zero fanfare or pompous preaching. These journalists are simply doing their job and attempting to tell a vital, damming story. Even when it's characters get overworked and angry about the various road blocks in their way, it's always in service of the story they are working on. They aren't looking to change the world or get credit for exposing a story that needs exposing. They simply want this story told for the victims' sake and sanity and to deter future victims.
