Journalist have been the inspiration of numerous films, going from the best of them "All the President¬¥s Men" to the dark and overlooked "Zodiac", so what does "Spotlight" offers that would make it stand out? The answer is the shocking/disturbing nature of its subject matter. 
The film tells the true events that lead up to the publication an investigation regarding numerous Catholic Church child abuse cases in Boston, by the investigation team "Spotlight" of the Boston Globe Newspaper. 
Just by taking a look to the cast this film has, I was interested in watching this film as most of these actors I really like, and this film didn't disappoint me. "Spotlight" counts with solid acting by its entire impressive cast (even though most of them are wasted in bland roles) with the standout being Mark Ruffalo stealing every scene he is in, a sharply written screenplay that never loses its realism, some good doses of comedy, a simple piano based score that works when its used, a flat but beautiful cinematography, McCarthy's directing is focused and straightforward, which is exactly what's need in this story; the story is shocking and will send chills to you spine as it goes along, a slow pacing that's allows the audience to understand the magnitude of the subject, editing that keeps you wanting to know more, the characters come across as real people, and the way they handled this extremely delicate, shocking, disturbing and extremely important subject matter is remarkable as they don't overplay it and they don't go to graphic scenes, they just say what's relevant and show how it destroy hundreds of lives. But even if this film has a lot of greatness, it's greatest element (the storytelling) is also is biggest flaw as the characters are forgettable and most of them lack personality, thus making this film a hollow film to watch.
"Spotlight" is a well-made, and engaging film but is overall forgettable. It handles its subject matter wisely and will start interesting conversations. Undeniably one of the best films of 2015 (possibly the best), it is definitely worth watching.
