I came into this film thinking it was going to be slow and a struggle to get through. Boy was I wrong! This is easily one of the best films I've seen so far in this young year. Spotlight is a research team for the Boston Glove that investigate things in more depth. When new editor in chief Marty Baron (Liev Schreiber) comes to the Globe he wants the newspaper to mean something again. He instructs Spotlights chief Walter Robinson (Michael Keaton) along with his team made up of the veteran Matt Carroll (Brian d'Arcy James), the only female on the team Sacha Pfeiffer (Rachel McAdams) and then the one always looking for the truth Mike Rezendes (Mark Ruffalo). Together Robinson has them look into the molestation charges and cover up by the Catholic church in the Boston area. Soon enough they begin to uncover more and more leading to an ever bigger issue that doesn't just affect Boston, but possible the whole world. The film also stars Stanley Tucci as Mitchell Garabedian a lawyer that is fighting the church and also John Slattery as a fellow editor named Ben Bradlee Jr who helps to uncover what's going on. The movies performances are absolutely fantastic. You feel for the characters and the pacing moves it along quite well. I never once was bored watching this regardless of some of the very morbid storyline features. Overall, fantastic film that I highly recommend anyone give a look!
