Powerful, yet restrained, effective, thought-provoking and tense, Spotlight is a flawless example of what a perfect drama & thriller should be. A wonderful depiction of what investigative journalism is and how to make this right into a movie, Tom McCarthy's gem is a already and instant classic that easily could be considered as one of the biggest favorites at this year's Oscars. 

Based on the true story of how the so called "Spotlight" team of The Boston Globe investigated and uncovered the decade-long continuous sexual abuse in the Catholic Church in Boston, the movie impresses with its overall approach towards the story and the facts. Just like the team of journalist which handled the topic, director Tom McCarthy makes sure that the movie does the same. Restrained, focused, slow, but steadily developed, the story builds up the tension and the thrills to a sky-high level even without a single act of violence. It is a journalist drama that simply depicts how a true investigative journalism should be conducted and everyone who is or feels himself connected to the world of media, communications and journalism will be completely delighted with this movie. Another achievement of director Tom McCarthy is the fact that even though this is a journalist drama, there is enough attention paid to the victims. The multiple victims are not dehumanized as persons of journalistic interest, but do share their stories in a way that nobody, even a devoted, skeptic catholic, could remain untouched. 

In addition to the incredible way of handling the story, the cast ensemble of Spotlight is what also turns this movie into a classic. Michael Keaton, Marc Ruffalo, Rachel McAdams, Live Schreiber and the rest, are amazing. Without depicting their characters as "investigative" heroes, all of them are just professionals and human beings. They are people who are devoted to their jobs, who make mistakes, who have their concerns, worries and doubts. Special attention should be paid to the trio Keaton- Ruffalo - Schreiber. Michael Keaton has a commanding presence and absorbs the indirect tension which different institutions tried to put on his team. Marc Ruffalo's determination, energy and stubbornness won him an Oscar nomination for Best Male Supporting Act and even if he does not win it (if we consider Syvlester Stallone the favorite in the category), his performance will remain unforgettable. Last, but not least, some of the viewers (like myself) might be delighted by the performance and depiction of the executive editor Martin Baron (Liev Schreiber). Schreiber's character has the presence, behavior and charisma of what the perfect executive editor should be. 

In conclusion, Spotlight is definitely one of the top movies of 2015. A must see journalist drama, it will make you further explore this topic on the internet long after you see the final credits. With 6 Oscar nominations, currently it is almost a safe bet that this is the movie that could challenge the expected domination of The Revenant.
Nos encontramos con una de las mejores pel√≠culas sobre el periodismo en la historia del cine.  Junto a "All The President's Men", "Network" y "Good Night And Good Luck", aparece "Spotlight", la recreaci√≥n de la investigaci√≥n llevada a cabo por el Boston Globe sobre el abuso sexual infantil llevado a cabo en el  interior de la iglesia cat√≥lica.  El director Tom McCarthy (autor de las espl√©ndidas "The Station Agent", "The Visitor" y "Win Win") nos muestra de una forma emocionante, envolvente y contundente c√≥mo el equipo de investigaci√≥n de "Spotlight" va desenvolviendo esta madeja con implicaciones no solo religiosas, sino tambi√©n pol√≠ticas y econ√≥micas.  Los actores sabiamente le dan el protagonismo a la historia y eso los hace estupendos: Michael Keaton, Mark Ruffalo, Rachel McAdams, Liev Schreiber, John Slattery, Stanley Tucci y Brian D'Arcy James no tienen falla: son perfectos.  "Spotlight" es una pel√≠cula formalmente sobresaliente, que logra cautivar al espectador de principio a fin y que denuncia algo que desde el 2001 no hemos querido enfrentar como debe ser. Para esto es el cine.
