Spotlight is on my top 5 favorite movies of 2015 list! Gracefully well made as it delves into sexual abuse scandal by Catholic priests in the Boston area.
Spotlight is the true story of an investigative branch of the Boston Globe who unearthed a massive cover-up among the Catholic Church and the astonishing number of child-molesting priests that were never brought to justice back in 2002 and with intense acting and riveting storytelling, it may be the best film based on journalism of all time. Directed by actor/writer Tom McCarthy with gusto, he certainly made a bold move taking on this project that paints what many go to for guidance in a really ugly light and you cringe more and more as you learn just how many priests were involved in this scandal. The Spotlight team is made up of character actor Brian d'Arcy James, and big-hitters: Rachel McAdams, Michael Keaton, and Mark Ruffalo in one of his strongest performances to date remaining subdued and believable with a boiling intensity in his vendetta for justice. The other supporting players are just as great with an unrecognizable Liev Schreiber, Mad Men's John Slattery, Stanley Tucci, and many others, rounding out a terrific ensemble cast that is more quality than quantity. If journalism interests you, this is your home run right here because it is not a flashy film at all and takes its time with the characters researching, interviewing, and writing this case for their paper and it's a great indication of how journalism can do some good as well! The film also plays fair and while it chastises the Church for burying it's secrets, it also shows that the reporters aren't perfect either and have made a few mistakes of their own, it would've been too easy to make this a witch-hunt film, but they thankfully don't go that route. This is a tense, realistic, and brainy drama about getting the facts straight and taking on one of the biggest cover-ups in history and it is immensely satisfying by the end and it's re-assuring to see the media in a positive light for a change.
I'm about to write the 5 words I never thought I would ever write about a move, THIS IS A PERFECT MOVIE!!!!!!  So, my wife and another couple who we are friends with decided to go to the movies, and my wife says let's watch this one I heard it was good.  I had not even seen the trailer for the movie, all I knew was that it had a killer cast.  Needless to say I went with no expectations, that is until I read what the movie is about while I was in the line.
This is a movie about journalists.  I say this because movies about journalists tend to be boring and tedious.  Never in a million years I thought that a movie about journalists (other than "All the President's Men") would be so exciting, engaging, thrilling, and powerful.
Lets start with the cast.  This is a stellar ensamble.  First of we have a fresh off an Academy Award nomination Michael Keaton (Robbie Robinson) doing some great work as the head of Spotlight.  You have Rachel McAdams, Bryan d'Arcy James, Liev Schrieber, and John Slattery, all ding great understated work.  It is not showy, it is just so good that you forget they are actors and you actually think this is a documentary.  Stanley Tucci with the small amount of screen time he is given manages (again) to pull you in to the point where you can't wait for the next time he is on screen.  Tucci truly is one of the best character actors there is.  
The real standout of this movie is Mark Ruffalo. Oh my God, what a performance! This is not a showy movie, so there isn't a lot of scenes where the actors can get all dramatic and showy, but he has three scenes near the end of the movie that take you from cheering and thinking "YEAH!" to welling up from the rawness of his performance.  Close to the end of the movie, the character having lost his faith we see him at the entrance of a church watching a choir rehearse and the look that he has just breaks you down.  All of the cast does great work, but he gives an award worthy performance.
I thought Tom McCarthy won't amaze me as he moved away from his usual stories . Yet, he did bring us a very well told story  with solid performances
Stunning acting (what a cast!), well-written and well-made movie. Plus based on bloodcurdling true story. I don't need anything more.
