I think it's crazy how many films are starting to come out about failures in trusted systems. It's so interesting to see this new information age we live in bring everything to light. Corruption can't hide anymore, not for long anyways. Interesting stuff.

I found this film to be really thought-provoking, and thrilling especially, based on the performances. Mark Ruffalo, in particular, really killed it - bringing so much passion and explosive energy to his character.

The story unwraps in such an intriguing way; the audience is placed in the same arena as the journalists and we remain gobsmacked throughout the entire uncovering of the church's exploitation of children in what seems to be such a trivial and primal urge. You really feel that betrayal that so many characters in the film express.

These "based on true story" films are so interesting, because it makes you wonder what the other side is, but something like this is painted so evenly that you wonder what the Catholic church's interest is in abusing adolescents and proceeding to protect such a widespread controversy, rather than eviscerating the offenders and trying to change the image. Maybe we're reaching a point that things are better now, but that's all thanks to the story in the film and the Boston Globe's bravery in standing up for others who were afraid to do so.

Definitely a rock-solid drama. Expect some Oscar noms.
