Brilliant - just brilliant! Very true to Boston
Very much of a piece with those 70s films about journalists fighting for the truth (namely All the President's Men, a masterpiece that this film clearly wants to be compared to), Spotlight is a solid, well-written, well-researched film that only moves into the inevitable self-important territory that comes with this material a few times ("We're going after the system!"). Here the quiet nature of the film isn't so much an admirable trait as much as an arbitrary characteristic of the proceedings, a subdued piece rather than a subtle one; the central search for evidence often feels less like McCarthy is deliberately seeking to make his own "important" film and more like he's diligently following the blueprints of other, similar, better movies, All the President's Men in particular. These quibbles aside, Spotlight is an excellent work dealing with an important subject, and while it's not the best film of the year, it definitely deserves to be included in that conversation.
