SPOTLIGHT is an undeniably powerful film, one whose subject matter is absolutely infuriating and disheartening, though if I'm being honest, it kind of coasts on that, and on the strength of the acting on display.  The filmmaking is very solid and workmanlike, but nowhere near the kind of bravura effort some in the critical community have argued it is; to me, it feels like an HBO movie, and you can take that any way you want.  Now, one could certainly make the case that to turn this story into some kind of flashy cinematic showcase would have been absolutely tone-deaf, and on a certain level I agree.  Yet, I still think the movie as a whole is a bit too restrained, a bit too low-key; I was captivated by the material, not so much by the cinema of it all.  The strongest element of the movie (unquestionably, in my mind) is the screenplay, which handles an insane amount of information, dates, names, and locations with apparent total ease, and it presents this information in ways that do not allow the facts to become jumbled up in the minds of the audience.  Just below the screenplay in importance are the cast members, each of whom do exemplary work, to a person being grounded and real.  Some might jump to Keaton or Ruffalo as the standouts, but Schreiber could be the movie's quiet MVP.  It's hard not to bring your own baggage to this story, and as a Catholic, it brought back all those things I felt when the actual story broke; the film is a powerful reminder... and also one I have no great desire to revisit.
Disturbing but unfortunately all too common true story about the tragedy of the Catholic church's coverup and reshuffling of molesting priests that continue their destruction elsewhere that goes all the way to the Vatican. This should be shocking but sadly we're all too used to it by now. Promise people they'll live forever and they will excuse anything. It drives home the adage: Good people do good, bad people do bad, but for a good person to do bad it takes religion. Although it is a wonderful film, it did not deserve Best Picture (there were several better IMO).
