A remarkable true story told in a perfectly unremarkable way. Spotlight probes into the Boston Globe's expos√É (C) of abuse in the Catholic Church with razor-sharp dialogue and a compelling team of characters behind the news desk, but everything else feels unfortunately phoned-in. The story is predictable, Tom McCarthy's direction is dry and pedestrian (after the tenth dramatic dolly in, I couldn't help but roll my eyes), and its finger-wagging to the audience is so on the nose I felt like I was being punched in the face. And to be frank, the supporting cast is so stuffed full of old, white men I had to keep a list of who was who.

Despite my list of gripes, Spotlight is perfectly entertaining even if it is a shameless piece of Oscar bait.
