By myself
Spotlight's passionate but humble story is served exceptionally by its stellar cast, direction and writing, and the end result is a film that makes you want to drop everything and break the big new story.
The final 20 minutes of the film are a payoff, carefully constructed through the film, the only complain being the suspiction some twist is just put there for dramatic purpouses, devaluating the whole experience an inch. A great film anyways and everyone is really good, specially Liev Schreiber... I can see why it is the Oscar frontrunner, yet I don't think critics are judging only the film itself, but are also too influenced by the importance of the subject matter.
Utilitarian in approach, but ultimately satisfying in conclusion (they take on the Church and win for Christ's sake!), Spotlight boasts a solid cast, and a slow amping of tension as the insidious secrets of the powers-that-be in Boston are revealed. They were keeping it all to themselves to keep their so-called "good names" intact while the lives they claim to cherish and protect in God's name are ruined to save face. It's unraveled in a journalistic yarn that calls up "All The President's Men", but doesn't quite reaching those same heights.
A story that's worth telling. Spotlight is about the investigations behind accused priests who have allegedly molested young children. Its such a delicate and pretty disturbing subject to put on the screen but the movie executed it so well. I really enjoyed this film. Its star filled cast including Mark Ruffalo, Rachel McAdams, Michael Keaton, Liev Schrieber, and Stanley Tucci, bring expeirence and add class to the film. Every individual gives a great performance and makes their character very believable. But Mark Ruffalo stands out the most. I felt his was more ecstatic and flowing. Another Oscar worthy performance from him. The direction in the film is great. Behind a strong screenplay, Tom McCarthy does a stellar job at creating a lively atmosphere about the world of journalism. It's compelling sorry really keeps you concerned with that matter at hand. My biggest issue with Spotlight although I wasn't completely bothered by it is the pace. I felt the film had a lot of incidents in which there were big scenes the movie slowed down. It couldn't keep a steady moving rate of intensity. Audiences will also have trouble keeping track of numerous names that is hard to follow.  Overall Spotlight was wonderful. It told the story so well that it made the movie very intriguing. This is definitely one of the best all around films of 2015. If you're looking for a movie that is well written, acted and has a meaningful story, watch Spotlight.
great coverage on a difficult subject
"How do you say no to God? This isn't just physical abuse; it's spiritual abuse." Surprisingly, the headline-grabbing Catholic Church sex scandal is not even the real focus of this powerhouse display of acting and directing. Yes, the abuses are horrendous, even when they are just being spoken and not shown. However, the true star of Spotlight is an intense and loving look at the nearly-lost art of the journalistic process. McCarthy directs with a refreshing lack of glamour or melodrama, leaving us with this question: if our "heroes" succeed here, who really wins?
An interesting, well acted and engaging film about seeking truth and justice.
Yet another astounding piece of cinema making its way to us just as the year comes to a close. Spotlight is the slow burning but riveting tale of the monolithic Boston Globe, based on a true story, when a small team within the paper, called Spotlight, are forced to drop their current investigation and their laid back attitude, in favor of a more audacious and high pressured investigation into molestation in the catholic church, they soon find that not only are their fears true, but uncover a plethora of cases and resistance from the church itself. Spotlight could easily be a David Fincher moment, brimming with brilliant character pieces, rooted in american style and oozing intrigue from the work go, and Tom McCarthy even borrows from Fincher's, Zodiac, in one or more shots. However McCarthy decides to fight back the darkness, somewhat, and leave us with a daunting but uplifting piece, that by the end will completely envelop you. Its a slow burning affair, with not a lot going on, subdued performances, with the exception of Ruffalo and nothing to flashy in the visual department, McCarthy is clearly letting the story and his script do all the heavy lifting and for the briefest of moments the film does feel a little lost to begin with. By the time the 2nd act comes around, not only have we lost ourselves in a weighty investigation, but there is a fare share of excellent drama and performance to go about. The cast are all terrific, everyone from Keaton, Schrieber, Crudup, McAdams, Tucci and Slattery all do some solid work, grounding the lifeblood of the Globe and making the piece feel extremely human and unlike an Oscar nomination, however its Mark Ruffalo's completely riveting and game changing performance that turns this cast and indeed film from a good time, into a great time. He just becomes a character, even with his, huge stature as the Hulk, Ruffalo is fearless and capable of completely bypassing any connection with his CGI counterpart, by just deeply rooting himself in good old fashioned performance, from mannerisms to accent, really lending a sense of realism to the whole affair. Its a great picture all around, and thats Spotlights biggest flaw, if you can call it that, it appears to play it safe. The film takes quite a bit of time to start leaving you a little more time than you want, to begin to pick apart the film itself, by the end you will really love the final product but will not be able to shake the feeling that McCarthy may have played this one, just a little too safe. Its understandable given the content but in this case the careful approach can be felt by the final frame. It's a solid effort, a film more subdued and down scaled than a lot of others on offer this year, strongly recommend.
An incredible and heart-wrenching movie about the horrible history of abuse and systemic cover up associated with the Catholic Church.
Spotlight is a very compelling movie, with an engaging plot and fascinating mystery thriller. It was great performances all around, but Mark Ruffalo especially stood out from the ensemble. The direction by Tom McCarthy was excellent, despite his previous directorial credits. This film explored very interesting themes of morality and ethics, and was also respectful of the religion of Christianity while pointing out issues in the institution of the church. However, the movie does drag at parts and could have been tightened up a bit...

