For anyone unfamiliar with the Catholic church child molestation scandals of the last 20 years this provides great insight into the issue and is at the same time a disturbing look at institutional cover-uppery at its worst!
Wow - the cover up of all cover ups... and the sad thing is, it's a true story.
Must see film.  Not only for the corruption of institutions, but the importance of a free press.  I followed this story actively in the NYT, but was still shocked at the depth of the problem and the church's coverup.  I rue not reading the original spotlight article when published.
Spotlight is a gripping drama of real-life people braving a storm in search of the truth. It's story is at times difficult to believe was based on facts, but with a captivating screenplay, a no-holds-barred approach to the harsh reality of said story and committed performances by all its players, you believe that you could watch a documentary or video-journal of the events as they took place. Set in in Boston in 2001 right before and going through 9/11, Spotlight's much discussed story is thus: for over 30 years, priests of the Catholic Church have been abusing children without law officials doing so much as letting people discuss it. Such a story in this day and age could sound like a punch-line for a joke, but at the time the story was breaking, it is easy to see how jarring this was to realize. In such a tight-knit community as in Boston, it would be easy for priests, the high and mighty disciples of God who the common folk look up to and strive to please, to cover something up like this. Something had to be done as demonstrated in the film. The performances are all of the charts and very well thought out. There isn't anyone to single out really because of how much of an ensemble piece the movie is, with all these distinguished and recognizable actors losing themselves in their roles, which is a testament to the commitment put into this project. A brilliantly conceived and executed film with an instant draw.
A rock-solid true story drama. Well-written and acted.
in theater with Boston sweatshirt sobbing.
VIEWS ON FILM review by Jesse Burleson

"I wanna keep digging" quips the character of Walter Robinson (Michael Keaton), a well respected reporter at Beantown's most heralded newspaper. What can I say, I "dug" all 128 minutes of the vehicle I'm about to review.

Anyway, for all Academy Award purposes and historical insight, Spotlight is the quintessential best picture nominee. It's secure, by the book filmmaking and that doesn't hurt it in any way. 1976 had All the President's Men, 1981 had Absence of Malice, 2007 had Zodiac, and now 2015 brings us "Light". All these films have one thing in common. They are dialogue-driven, feed off paranoia, and resound in crowded newsrooms. "Nose goes" gets a nose for the news. Natch!

Taking place in the early 2000's and helmed by director Tom McCarthy, Spotlight moves along like a jack rabbit. Yeah this flick is talky but it never comes off as insipid. There are a lot of continuity cuts between scenes, ensemble acting (where everyone helps each other out) of the highest order, and crackling intrigue inhabiting every frame. Alongside his previous endeavor Birdman, "Light's" lead in Michael Keaton, is now two for two. His co-star (Mark Ruffalo) who got nominated for a supporting role via 2014's Foxcatcher, is also batting 1.000.

So yeah there might be a repetition in Spotlight involving every (news reporter) caricature interrogating a victim and/or a suspect. No matter. This Open Road Films release rings true because Josh Singer's screenplay is tight and engrossing. What we have amongst the muck, is the best movie of the year (so far). And just like one of my other top picks (2015's Black Mass), the city of Boston swallows the proceedings whole as if Michael Phelps decided to inhale tons of hot dogs. You want to see actual events depicted that involve a massive cover-up among the Roman Catholic priests? You'll get that in "Light". You want the 9/11 attacks to be used effectively as a backdrop? You'll get that as well. You wanna witness a small investigative team unravel the secrets behind so many young churchgoers getting molested? It's all there. And do you want to revel in having the Boston Globe be the locale where all the news shtick goes down? Prego. Finally, do you want a cast that includes Liev Schreiber, Stanley Tucci, Rachel McAdams, and Billy Crudup? Who wouldn't.

All in all, Spotlight involves behind-the-scenes preoccupation in small rooms and quiet, open spaces. Every nuance between the troupers sticks. With its disciplined magnetism and critical darling demur, "Light" shines brightly. Rating: 4 stars.
Spotlight is an excellent, provocative film that tells a true story in a compelling way. I can see a general audience finding its subject matter somewhat dry, but I was thrilled not only by the story the titular team attempts to uncover, but also by the process and part the media plays in bringing it into the public consciousness. We know now that the Catholic Church is irrevocably tarnished by this outrageous scandal, but Spotlight gives insight into the parties (intentional or otherwise) that buried it - and how they were able to do it for so long. 

My only complaint is that I wish more focus was given to the psychological defect underlying the normalized phenomenon of child abuse - something which I feel Doubt did very well. But the credence given to the experience of the survivors more than makes up for the lack of this angle.
I was apprehensive about seeing this, and now I cannot wait to see it again. It was an incredible story which conveyed the severity of what happened and what has been going on. I highly recommend this movie.
