A taut drama which evokes the very best of investigative journalism and stylized storytelling. This is an important movie, one that exposes how institutional power intimidates and imposes its will- until someone stands in defiance. It's yet another of the trademark social commentary films produced by the velvet glove of Jeff Skoll's Participant Media ("Bridge of Spies", "Charlie Wilson's War", "Cutizen Four", "good night. and good luck", "The Help", "An Inconvenient Truth" and "Syriana" amongst 70 films.)
A prestige picture of the first order, Spotlight concerns the real life story of a team of investigative journalists from The Boston Globe and their efforts to uncover the cataclysmic sexual abuse scandal in the Catholic Church.  Spotlight is primarily a character study and uses its runtime to showcase the talents of its ensemble cast.  Of particular note, Michael Keaton, Rachel McAdams, and Mark Ruffalo present relatable human characters whose motivations and backstories are unraveled in parallel with the abuse scandal.  The central theme is the power of intrepid, probing journalism in the face of overwhelming opposition, so in a sense it bears much in common with All the President's Men.  The heavy subject matter may shock some, but the presentation is quite objective and tasteful.  It does suffer from some overly indulgent and pretentious moments, but solid dramas can be forgiven for those.  I personally did not find it to be the year's best film, but I suspect it will be widely credited as such.
Brilliantly acted and honestly told, Spotlight walks the fine line between rich, entertaining drama, and solid, realistic fact telling.  A must watch for all.
Spotlight tastefully handles the sordid details of a sensitive subject; priests sexually abusing children and how the Catholic church engineered a complicated and complete cover up for decades.  Everyone knew this was going on but not to the extent that was finally discovered.  It is fact based and very well acted.  Don't miss this one even if you dislike the subject.  The good guys win!
The screenplay and acting are a perfectly intriguing combo that leaves you in tune throughout the entire film. A troubling true story brought to life on screen. Well executed and best picture worthy indeed.
