Spotlight is one of the best investigative journalism films ever made. 

From the word go to the stunning facts shown at the end credits, Spotlight never loses pace, grittiness or it's ruthless approach. There's not a single dull moment anywhere whatsoever. Sticking to it's guns and based on cold hard facts, it re-enacts the sheer professionalism Boston Globe guys showed during their gruesome discovery and does so with impeccable grace and every emotion shown in the screen hits home with absolute precision. 

But all of these looked so spontaneous, seamless. Well, having Mark Ruffalo, Michael Keaton. Rachel McAdams. Liev Schreiber, John Slattery and Stanley Tucci in their ranks really helped the cause. Especially Mark Ruffalo. Steals the show time and time again.

Tom McCarthy's direction seemed lucid and vivid. In a film where you are working with facts and dialogues, you probably should never let the pace down or let the grip loosen even when it is so easy to do just that(Fincher's Zodiac, arguably, is a good example of a dialogue based, fact ridden film going slow, take it easy, yet making an positive impact. But that's probably always not the case.). Tom McCarthy recognized this and took the high road.

With two Golden Globe nominations, Spotlight surely will have more accolades in it's way. And it deserves every one of them.
