This movie works as a good mystery or thriller even though the outcome is known. The top notch performances and taut script keeps it moving along at a steady pace. Overall it left me feeling angry (because very little has changed) and nostalgic. Nostalgic - for back in the day when newspapers really mattered (because it wasn't about personalities looking to become media darlings, or to get a headlining tv show or write a book. It was about a team doing the work and telling important stories). Nostalgic - for back when movies made you feel something, and it wasn't about cute one liners or special effects. Nostalgic - for a time we may never see again when we thought our great institutions cared not just about us but especially about our children. Now we know it's about maintaining the status quo at all cost not and perpetuating their power. Nostalgic - for my youth when dressing up and going to church was important and uplifting (and yes, we thought priests were gods as someone in the movie says) - but alas, not even a rock star pope will bring me back to the Catholic Church.
A movie like this shouldn't be as interesting as it was, but with a neat flawless cast and pulse pounding mystery throughout, Spotlight is one of the years best films by a mile and a half.

