This is a film I will come back quite soon. It's intelligent, the acting is very good (with the Keaton and especially Ruffalo being the MVP's, but Rachel McAdams, Live Schreiber and Stanley Tucci doing great work) but what I really respect about this film is its ambition to focus on the work done, on the issue at hand without glorifying the journalists and without making a fuss about their big victory. I, as a viewer, felt as close to unearthing the scandal and realizing its scope and the personal tragedies related to it as the journalists on the Spotlight team. I also responded to the economy of the cinematic approach (there's not one wasted scene, not one wasted shot) and the refusal to allow sentiment and big dramatic moments associated with such films to make it into the film and turn it into an overblown self-congratulary melodrama.
Quite moving. And important. Great acting, especially Ruffalo. I thought the story was told really well. At the end, I am both very angry and very sad and unsure of which emotion is stronger.
It's tough for me to say exactly why Spotlight worked for me.  There's nothing spectacular that really stands out about it, and in many other films that tried the same style I'd call it boring and pedestrian.  Somehow though, Spotlight pulls it off.  It's plays things simple, and maybe that's what makes it work.  It's the subtlety of it all that makes the whole thing work.  The facts are big, but reactions are subtle, and that makes it all feel more genuine.
I don't think there's anything very special about Spotlight's directing (which makes this year's Oscar nominations pretty surprising), but what really makes the movie work are the performances and the script.    I recognized a lot of the actors at first, but pretty quickly forgot about their past roles and just saw them as people.  They discover horrific details about the catholic sex abuse scandal, but each new reveal doesn't lead them to some huge Oscar-bait outburst, but a more genuine response.  Oftentimes they are simply speechless, and that feels very real.  The script is also great.  It drops you right in the middle of things, these events have already been happening for a while, but it doesn't take long to catch up and it respects you enough to expect that you can.  There was never any point when I was really bored by the movie.
If I have an outright criticism of the movie it's that I maybe would have liked more information, but I don't think that's this movies job.  It tells a very specific perspective of the events unfolding, it would just be nice if there were other movies that gave more perspective.  As this singular perspective though, it works really well.  There's not a lot of character development or anything like that, it's really just the investigation, but that's more than enough to carry the film.  If watching news reporters investigate a story isn't your thing, I get it, it's not going to be riveting for everyone, but it was for me.  I can't really pinpoint the magic ingredient that made Spotlight work so well, but damnit all it really did work so damn well.
A solid story - much in the style of Argo...
Best movie on journalism since all the presidents men
"Spotlight" is about the team of investigative reporters of the Boston Globe that goes by the same name who uncovered the child molestation and cover up scandal by the clergy of the local Catholic Archdiocese. The reporting won the team the 2003 Pulitzer Prize.

"Spotlight" is an ode to investigative reporting that focuses on accuracy, fact checking and restraint in publishing a story until all the facts and circumstances have been fully covered. It is a discipline and an art form that is almost lost in today's world of journalism where the focus have been subverted to get higher ratings (TV), keep subscribers and maintain readership (print media) or to please advertisers (both).

The film features a superb cast that includes Mark Ruffalo, Michael Keaton, Rachel McAdams, Liev Schreiber, John Slattery and Stanley Tucci, to name a few. The ensemble acting is magnificent. As to the story, it is told with meticulous attention to detail.

"Spotlight" reminds us of "All The President's Men", the 1976 film that focused on the Watergate scandal. But more importantly, this film shows what true and hard-working journalists can accomplish when the focus is on the victims - even if it means taking on an institution that has power, money and resources. It is about performing due diligence and telling an accurate story that, in the end, looks at a system that allowed a cover up to happen.
If I could give this 10 stars, I would. Just extraordinary. Everyone should see this. Everyone.
It amazes me this disgusting organization is still in business, considering the entire entity, including its highest ranking members all the way up to Pope Benedict consciously tried to hide the rape of children. Yet, people continue to fund its operations. I wonder what their imaginary God would say about persons contributing money weekly to an organization whose cottage industry is the rape of children and its subsequent cover-up.
Definitely deserved Best Picture.
Phenomenal movie. The power and quality of this movie comes from its devotion to tell the true story down to nearly every last detail, whether its running to the courthouse as it's closing to get documents for the story, or calling out to sources and getting rejected, or even the accents each character has. The screenplay does well to show the hard work the Spotlight team did to put together the horrible story they discovered, and the performances from its cast are great, especially Ruffalo. As a journalist, this is yet another incredible film that honors the profession and makes me proud to be one.
