It seems every 5-10 years there seems to be an All the Presidents Men type of film that comes out circling around a very important news story of the time or a time, ranging from Michael Mann's the Insider regarding the 60 Minutes breaking of the insider info of the Tobacco Industry,or Zodiac which focuses on the Zodiac investigation by the Chronicle and San Fran police department in the late 70's. In this case, it is the buried for too long story of the sexual abuse scandal that originated in Boston which is a huge catholic hub that latter spread around the whole globe, at the beginning of the last decade and the Boston Globe Spotlight researchers who ended up picking up the story by their new editor when it was a much smaller case. Very much about the writting and the ensemble cast with very award worthy performances by both Keaton and Ruffalo, Spotlight gradually unfurls all the story threads as the case develops from one possibly lead to many without overplaying its hand and doesnt make things too showey with music, letting the emotion and information pretty much speak for itself as the audience discovers the scope of the misdeads by the church. A for sure Academy Award contender and was very worthy of being a contender for the audience award at TIFF 2015. A great return to form for Mccarthy after the stumble that was the Cobbler.
