There are some really good movies that you simply like to watch over and over again, and then there are some like Spotlight while very good, I don't think I want to see ever again.  Spotlight is very well written and acted and directed, so much so you feel like you are back in 2001 when this behavior by some priests was uncovered by the Boston Globe.  As the husband to a Catholic wife and father to Catholic children and son to a Catholic mom, I grieve alongside them at all that came forward through this investigation, and is why I don't think I want to sit through this movie again.  I was riveted and engaged was the story unfolded and surely sympathized with the victims as their stories were told.  However, the pure subject matter is hard for me to handle more then one viewing.  It's not that any of the behavior was shown on the screen, just the knowledge of the subject matter is enough for me.  This is a worthy best picture candidate, but I sure don't want it to win.
