Serves to remind us why investigative journalism is so important.
Inspired casting and pitch perfect scripting make Spotlight an astounding achievement.  Spotlight adds to a long list of great investigative procedurals such as All The Presidents Men, The Insider and Zodiac.  This film however, gets at something more profound, and that is journalism as moral imperative.  What obligations do journalists have to investigate a possible story?  If the press fails to act on possible leads or to take a story seriously or take on a story because it might be too difficult, are they culpable for any harm that is done?  Where is that line drawn?  Spotlight invades a small investigative unit of the Boston Globe during one the city's most damning hours, the possible high level cover up of the molestation of thousands of children over the course of several decades by dozens of local priests and clergy, to answer these questions.  What really makes the film great is how Michael Keaton deals with the dilemma of bringing the story to live, while trying to square with the fact that the newspaper, under his watch, failed to uncover and report the story for decades despite mounting evidence of wrongdoing.  Its a truly dynamic piece of filmmaking that should find itself in the drivers seat for best picture, screenplay and supporting actor come Oscar time.
