Clean, crisp, and viscous. An eye opener that paints a complex story into a stand alone statement. Don't turn away because it's hard to watch or the blood will run over your hands.
From time to time, if we are so lucky, a movie comes along that stands out among the rest. Not because of how big the special effects are, how many jokes it has, or because of how many different groups of people took a liking to it because it pandered to their ideals; but rather because of how simple it is and how complex subject matter elevates it to a higher level of social prominence. This is the case for the new independent film Spotlight; a riveting story that shows how The Boston Globe brought to light one of the darkest stories in recent memory. I wont spoil too much about this film but I will say that this deals with the discovery of child molestation in the Catholic Church and how one newspaper fought to bring light to this horrific issue. There is simply not one thing I could see wrong with this film so lets dive in and talk about where this movie excels. The main area this movie succeeds is in how subdued the acting is as well as the major scenes. The cast here includes award worth performances form Michael Keaton, Mark Ruffalo, Rachel McAddams, and Liev Schrieber. They make up the primary cast here and their performances are above exemplary. Each actor delivers strong performances and never brings the element of melodrama to their scenes. It would have been easy for them to scream and shout to the news they discover but they all show multiple emotions at the same time that makes this movie feel more real than any other movie I have seen since 12 Years a Slave. The writing here is equally powerful highlighting terrific dialogue as well as scenes that will crawl under your skin and keep you invested throughout the film. The big scenes in the film are very subdued in their delivery. The lack of musical score in some parts even elevates them to new heights as they let the dialogue sink in rather than musical swells. The dialogue also carries weight with every scene that we as movie goers simply aren't used to anymore. The climax of the film in particular comes form the dialogue rather than set pieces of arrests or anything else. Director Tom McCarthy also delivers some of the finest scenes shot this year. His direction, along with outstanding cinematography, blend together perfectly for a crisp view of the Boston Globe building as well as Boston as a whole. This movie's setting in Boston also serves as a strong point here. We are constantly reminded of how tight knit the city is and even goes as far as to why a story like this is so prominent and elevates the film even further in terms of drama as well as suspense. Overall I can not possibly praise Spotlight enough. It takes on of the darkest story and handles it with care and delivers one of the finest films in years. Everything works here and I implore all of you to go and see this film when you can.
Every single thing about this story and film is award worthy, important and worth seeing.  It's hard.  It's revolting.  It's infuriating.  It must be known.
