This film was really good, and arguably one of the best this year. What is astonishing is this film is just acting. There are no actions scenes to speak of, and every scene is carried by the actors and actresses' performance. In a sense this film is very similar to "All the Presidents Men" in regards how the reporters pursue a story, and showing the amount of work it took. This scenes are mostly carried by the reporting crew, and each person did a great job portraying their characters. Beyond the main reporting crew, the supporting characters were amazing as well. Despite Liev Schreiber and John Slattery getting limited time, but both of them put in amazing performances in their respective roles. The only complaint, and it's not a major complaint at all, is the movie starts out slow. It takes about 20 minutes for the movie to get moving in regards to pursuing the story. Overall it works, but it does start out slow. 

Finally as a Catholic I should mention this, but the movie did a great job not bashing the religion or making it into a 2 hour anti-Catholic piece. It simply portrayed what happen as it did without an additional narrative added, and the movie was more about the actual reporters trying to make sure what they report is the entire truth.
