I'm an ex-Catholic Atheist, and I saw this movie with a Jewish friend. When it was over, I told him, "I can never understand what it's like to be Jewish, and you can never understand what it's like to be Catholic." I was not comparing the darkness of my bruises with his, I merely meant that we all carry our own special forms of spiritual burden. The impact of the parish priest on a faithful Catholic child is profound. These men were our spiritual heroes. I recognized on a deeply resonating level the impact of the depth of betrayal and scarring these monsters perpetrated on thousands of innocent children. 

I mean like burn victim-level scarring. 

The only question was how graphically this movie would portray the predations of these priests. Spotlight is actually quite restrained in this regard. Although the movie is essentially about the journalistic process - "how I got that story" - director Tom McCarthy could have easily gone whole hog with vivid flashback scenes. Thankfully, he didn't. He told two stories - two out of thousands - with simple, fact-based spoken descriptions of the priestly predations. It was restrained, and more than sufficient. After all, it's unlikely anyone seeing the movie doesn't know about the scandal. We come to this movie with ready fury, we hardly need convincing. 

Excellent performances across the board. This story could not have been told more clearly and more effectively. I think the moviemakers approached it with a sense of obligation to history to tell the story as  truthfully as possible, without varnish or hype. The truth is unthinkable enough.
Smart, gripping, and incredibly well acted, Spotlight is filled with details of its factual story, strong representations of its real-life subjects and news reporters, and even stronger performances by Michael Keaton, Mark Ruffalo, Rachel McAdams, and Stanley Tucci, it works as a dramatization of the actual event and as a movie!
