Spotlight is one of those films that does exactly what it seeks to do without flaw, making you interested and believe a real life story. Once I got engaged with the material and the characters I never questioned what was happening, it felt like I was watching history of the Catholic church abuse scandal unfold before my eyes.

This is done primarily through the world class talent that delivers on all fronts: Keaton, Ruffalo, Tucci, McAdams. I was particularly impressed with the smaller role of Liev Schreiber as well, perfectly portraying a hesitant yet poignant leader. The only thing that detracts from the entirety of the film is the length, it felt long and a slew of characters made me notice the chair discomfort eventually. 

However this is still a gem of a movie that should be experienced not only because of it's superb execution, but because it tells an important story of real life events that affect the human beings that live around us in your community.
