Amazing.  The depth of the cover up was immense, and Boston was only scratching the surface.
A perfectly scripted and perfectly paced film displays the horrible guilt that comes with true self-examination. On one side, the relatively new institution of the American free press. On the other side, the two-millennia old institution of the Roman Catholic Church. On paper, it sounds like a conspiracy of epic proportions, and when you relive these events through these eyes, the implication becomes that much more heartbreaking: we knew, and did nothing. Why? Because how dare we challenge something that has been around for two thousand years? But as the events of the film show, it takes outsiders to hold the mirror to ourselves so that we can accept the truth.
Spotlight is the polar opposite of The Revenant when it comes to storytelling, and that is not a bad thing in the least. The two films act as pillars of filmmaking in 2015. One uses visual splendor to draw the viewer in to the film, while stark violence and raw emotions allow the audience to relate to the characters. The other builds up a rapport with the viewers through realistic and relatable dialogue, about a subject that needs to be talked about and explored with characters that we genuinely like based on their personalities and not their actions alone. Both are excellent, they just differ greatly. Spotlight covers the topic of the journalism team that uncovered the sexual abuse cover up taking place in Boston churches and the importance of investigative journalism as a whole. With a cast lined from back to front with top performers such as Mark Ruffalo, Michael Keaton and John Slattery, it is brimming with characters that we root for, but also believe to be real people. The story required a grounded approach, one that wasn't heavy handed, and Spotlight delivers. You won't find a grandiose score, or long takes to emphasize moments. Everything here is earned based on the performances and subject matter alone, and it is refreshing. In a season filled with Oscar hopefuls, this film feels genuine. If you haven't already, put Spotlight at the top of your must watch list. 5 out of 5 stars.
There isn't really a bad performance in "Spotlight", even the extras are good, and the movie fully displays how compelling and sad the situation is without being overwhelming. A must see for just about everyone
