Every Wednesday "The Cinema Arts Theater", a nearby movie theater, offers seniors over 65 entrance to any movie for $5. Though low budget & completely independent (it was started by 2 retired Foreign Service Officers in the 1980s) the theater has a surprisingly strong line-up of movie choices.  This week they are showing 8 movies, including "Spotlight", "Room",  "Bridge of Spies", Brooklyn", "Specter", "Suffragate", that "Hunger Games" flick and a few others.  

Anyhow I went to the 2:30PM showing of "Spotlight" because a) it received a 98% from critics and 96% from audiences on the Rotten Tomatoes" 'Tomato-meter' ... and b) because I was raised in Catholic schools. Apparently many other seniors in our area had gotten the word that it was/is a good movie because about half of the seats in the theater were filled with seniors like myself.  

I attend maybe 5 movies a year at this theater during 'seniors' day', but this was the first time that the audience spontaneously clapped and cheered at the conclusion of the film.  The movie is riveting.  Like "All the President's Men", it tells the true story of a newspaper's investigative reporting of a major scandal.  But unlike "All the  President's Men",  I did not know in advance the ending or "the rest of the story".   [I also did not know that Ben Bradley was at the Boston Globe in 2001 supervising the development of this story as he had done at the Washington Post during the Watergate scandal that brought down Nixon.]  

"Spotlight" was the name of the little, 4 person investigative unit at the Boston Globe that broke the story of rampant, criminal sexual abuse of minors by Boston area priests ... and, more importantly, the criminal cover up of the abuse by the Catholic Church and Boston city government authorities.  The casting, acting, direction, editing, etc. were all excellent.  I didn't even notice the music, but that suggests it didn't get in the way of the intense story which is the center of the film.  A few times I caught myself tensed up, and I had to remind myself to breath.

For me the most shocking revelation came after the film concluded, and the screen was filled with a written narrative that explained what happened after the Boston Globe published it's revelations.

I highly recommend it, especially for anyone raised as a Catholic.
If you want to see an exquisitely done homage to real life heroes, this is your film.
