Fascinating journalistic procedural with a well picked cast.  But the most powerful acting comes from the actors chosen to play the victims of childhood abuse: ALL excel from beginning to end.
Did you know the Catholic Church has been complicit in thousands of sexual abuse scandals?  If somehow that's news to you, then the movie might be riveting, but I can't help but feel the drama is supposed to come from the revelation of information that's been common knowledge for over a decade.  I feel like a dunce any time a movie seems to get unanimous rave reviews while I remain unaffected, but I'm just not sure how this was supposed to be interesting.  Despite what almost everyone says, the acting is not electrifying; it is, like everything else in this movie, simply competent and functional. (Rachel McAdams's delivery seems particularly forced.)  The standout, however, is Liev Schreiber, who paradoxically generates the most interest and charisma through a character who essentially has no personality.
But where was the drama in this movie?  The Spotlight team makes a lot of phone calls, conducts a lot of interviews, and looks over a lot of documents.  That's the movie.  There's no arc.  As it unspools, you find that the sexual abuse scandal is massive and involves more and more people, but again, we already knew that.  There isn't any story telling to speak of, just procedural what-have-you to reach a foregone conclusion.
So if your idea of a taught thriller consists of characters talking to other characters whose identity and/or importance isn't really described; or if you like seeing people read documents, the contents and importance of which aren't fully explained; or if you're in the mood to see characters tackle a big problem that honestly doesn't really affect their welfare and puts very little at stake...then for you, this may be Best Picture 2016.
