"Spotlight" is a compelling, thoughtful look at the Catholic Church's attempt to cover-up its clergymen's molesting of children back in the early 2000's. A group of Boston Globe reporters, led by Michael Keaton, try to get to the bottom of the cover-up. What ensues is a provocative but admittedly fascinating look at how the molestation plague was endemic to the entire Catholic Church from the top-down. The film manages to address this sensitive subject matter without resorting to heavy-handed directing or confirmation bias, The film is a bit slanted against the Church but does so in a way that maintains journalistic integrity and sticks to the facts, not speculation. It is also interesting to see how a story is put together and how sometimes pervasive subject matter has to come to the fore to keep the masses informed. A smart look at the ethics of journalism and sure to turn heads come Oscar time ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------- A-
