It was almost everything I love about movies like this, a riveting and enlightening way to present the story of what happened, to be educated about an important historical event that I may have known about from the news but did not know the full story.  I left off a star because I felt after the long build up and crescendo to the big moment of finally putting the story out - I was left wondering where the climax was - the ending seemed rather chopped off. They released the story, went into the office to discover calls ringing off the hook, and then the movie was over and the lights came up.  Maybe a little more of the explosive reaction of the public and the way the news hit everyone (possibly the church's reaction too?), rather than just phones ringing?  I felt like it was an ending more reliant on the audience supplying their own climax by recalling each in our own minds and emotions the way we remember the news exploding on the scene at the time, rather than actually depicting it.   There was a lot more intensity, drama and emotion displayed in the reporters and others on their way to discovering and producing the expose than when they finally unleashed it.
This film is one of the truly important ones to come along in 2015. It reveals a shameful secret of the Catholic Church; not so much in the acts themselves (that are bad enough) but in the institutional cover-up by the hierarchy that good Catholics expect to guarantee the church's integrity. At the same time, it is a story of the tenacity of a major US Newspaper, the Boston Globe. In largely Catholic Boston, taking on the Catholic church is no mean task, but the paper does so. All of the performances are done with dedication and care--not with the over-acting that some of the actors have portrayed in other films. One of the truly good films of 2015.
Handling its extremely sensitive subject matter with a care not known to typical Hollywood sensationalism, "Spotlight" maintains its integrity despite the sell of its star studded cast. It is a thriller that relies on a combination of superb acting and screenwriting instead of a fast-paced score and editing tricks. As a result, it is captivating throughout, shining a light on a true human tragedy that, as the film knows, will likely continue to be overlooked as long as someone is willing to overlook it.
Absorbing and well-acted drama that deals with an important topic with intelligence. Spotlight is sure to be a heavy awards contender in the acting and Best Picture categories. This is smart and highly engaging filmmaking if a bit anti-climactic. Rating: 84
