If you're not a journalist, I implore you to see "Spotlight," the movie about the Boston Globe's uncovering of the Catholic Church abuse scandal. (I assume all the journalists are already on it.) For one, it's just an excellent movie. But more importantly, it shows how great journalism is done. It's not flashy or glamorous; it's hard work. It's making phone calls and knocking on doors and tracking down information and poring over records. This isn't something aggregation news sites or bloggers are going to do. You're not going to get it from sources' tweets. It takes time and resources -- something fewer and fewer news media organizations are willing to invest in. And that's troubling for all of us because people and institutions who are allowed to operate in darkness (even those as venerated and trusted as the Catholic Church) are likely to abuse their power, sooner or later. Those abuses can cost anything from taxpayers' money to people's lives. We need good journalism to help keep officials, institutions and governments accountable. This movie helps show how that's done and why it's so important for us to support such journalism.
Amazing acting from everyone. The experience of watching this movie is like being punched in the gut repeatedly. But it's necessary. I hope it gets the Oscar because it's such an important story. I don't know that anything could really be spoiled for this movie, but the most important message to me is about how easy it is as a society to instinctively defend something that has both good and bad elements. It's okay to attack the bad parts--hell, it's our moral duty to go after the bad parts, as difficult as that is.
This is a great movie! It's well acted, moves at a good pace, yet still feels real.
Great movie, this needs to be seen by a lot of people so studios keep making high quality stuff like this. We get enough blow-em up stuff, this is old-fashioned good movie making. It deals with a touchy subject, but it was really well done.
