SPOTLIGHT-2015(R)-Nov. 27.
BY:The Movie Guy.

Spotlight is the disturbing true story of one of the biggest cover-ups in U.S. history. The film opens in 2001, when allegations of child molestation by priests of the Catholic Church surface. A group of investigative reporters from The Boston Globe who collectively write in-depth stories for the "Spotlight" feature, begin investigating the abuse claims. When the team consisting of Matt Carroll (Brian d'Arcy James), Sacha Pfeiffer (Rachel McAdams), Michael Rezendes (Mark Ruffalo) & team leader Walter "Robby" Robinson (Michael Keaton) start asking some key questions they find that there are two distinct factions, those that are fighting to make the molestation known & find some justice for the victims such as lawyer for the victims, Mitchell Garabedian (Stanley Tucci) & those who are working to suppress any public acknowledgement such as lawyer Eric MacLish (Billy Crudup), who is quietly settling the cases out of court in cooperation with the Catholic Church. What also becomes too clear is the alarming duration & extent of the abuse & the church's full knowledge & its determined efforts to conceal the abuse & protect the offending priests. Director Tom McCarthy co-wrote the screenplay with Josh Singer, together they have exposed a dismal & terrible truth about the power of the Catholic Church to manipulate government, law & the faithful for its own purposes. The cast also features Liev Schreiber as The Boston Globe's new editor-in-chief Marty Baron, John Slattery as Ben Bradlee Jr., the Globe's former editor, & Richard Jenkins as Richard Sipe, a former priest turn psychotherapist who provides vital information to aid the investigation. The performances from this star-studded cast were remarkable. Three actors gave Oscar-worthy performances; Michael Keaton is riveting in the intensity of his dogged pursuits, Mark Ruffalo fully conveys the experience of the wrenching emotions that the reporters experience as they uncover the full extent & virtual institutionalization of the molestation. And as Mitchell Garabedian, Stanley Tucci illustrates that there are compassionate lawyers who care about the victims & will fight for them. Despite the uncomfortable subject matter, this is a film that everyone should see. CAN'T MISS FILM OF THE YEAR.
There was an easy way they could have told this story, all this went on and the Church did nothing. It's simple, but a story we already knew. Spotlight, however, explored the real story. Yes, the church knew, but so did half the town of Boston, including the Globe itself and the fact that Spotlight hit all those angles, including the self-incriminating ones, took this movie to another level.
Excellent and still shocking even over 10 years after the original news broke.
