An important movie, should be required viewing for everyone who has ever supported the Catholic church.  More than 240 "priests" raped and / or sexually assaulted children, yet the Catholic church covered up the crimes at the highest level.  Marty Baron, past editor of The Boston Globe and now editor of the Washington Post, should have been awarded a Nobel Peace Price for forcing these truths into the "Spotlight."
Spotlight is the true-story behind the 2002 expose into the Catholic Church's cover-up of decades of sexual abuse and it is unflinching in its focus and animated by its outrage, which is the best and worst part of this awards-caliber movie. Writer/director Tom McCarthy (The Station Agent, Win Win) is a splendid curator of unlikely movie families, and with Spotlight he follows the titular investigative team (Michael Keaton, Rachel McAdams, Mark Ruffalo, Brian d'Arcy James) at the Boston Globe as they go about their jobs. That's really about it. Over the course of two tightly packed hours, we watch as the Spotlight team chases down leads, goes through archives, interview subjects and know hen to push harder and when to fall back, and day-by-day build their case to expose the massive corruption within the Church. It's invigorating material and worthy of the careful and sincere reverence that McCarthy and co-writer Josh Singer have afforded, though the flurry of names can be difficult to keep track of. However, that's about the extent of the movie. We don't really get to know any of the journalists on much of a personal level or as a character; they are defined by their tenacity and competence. We don't get much time for reflection or contemplation on the subject, especially its psychological impact on a majority Catholic city/staff, and the culpability of those within systems of power that chose to ignore rather than accept the monstrous truth. I don't need more "movie moments" or emotionally manipulative flashbacks, per se. With its nose to the grindstone, Spotlight is an affecting and absorbing news article given life but it feels less like a fully formed movie of its own. It's confidently directed, written, acted, and executed to perfection, and I feel like a cad even grumbling, but the ceiling for this movie could have been set higher had the filmmakers widened its focus.

Nate's Grade: B+
With pretty much every reviewer touting Spotlight as the best film of 2015 and a favourite to win the Best Picture Academy Award, I came in expecting much from Tom McCarthy's film. Is Spotlight a good film? Yes. Was it the best from 2015? No. Spotlight is a good film about journalists trying uncover the scandal of priests molesting children in Boston. And that is what the film is ALL about. It tackles its subject matter seriously and with no-frills. It took it too seriously that it did not draw me in emotionally. Also, there also were too many characters and I did not get a chance to get to know them completely. Nevertheless, Spotlight is still an important film to watch.
Spotlight: This is the true story of the Pulitzer Prize-winning team of investigative reporters at The Boston Globe that, in 2002, broke the child sex abuse scandal and decades long coverup by the Archdiocese of Boston - a scandal that quickly snowballed into a worldwide crisis for the Catholic Church. Featuring an outstanding ensemble cast, this is a smart, important story about the dangers of quiet complicity and the importance of good investigative journalism. The shocking revelations of the scope of the abuse and the extent of the cover up within the church more than make up for a story that does, at times, lag a wee bit. Still, one of the year's best. A
