This is a pretty captivating movie that involves no explosions in terms of the performances or any stunts but is guided along with a very strong screenplay and a strong ensemble to play it out. Mark Ruffalo is great, Rachel McAdams is great and I hope people will see this and finally take her more seriously as many have just written her off in the past decade, other great performances include Brian D'Arcy James, Liev Schreiber, Billy Crudup, Len Cariou, Jamey Sheridan, and Michael Keaton who does a good job here but I have 0 clue why he is being propped up as this year's Best Supporting Actor winner when he does nothing really to qualify him for even a nomination. The two particular stand outs from the supporting ensemble are Stanley Tucci and John Slattery and Sheridan and Crudup get really great scenes to shine as well. The movie is like a train. You start to get on board in the first 20 min or so and then once the main focus of the story in presented, you are in for the ride until the very end if not even further than the end. I actually kind of want a spinoff TV series with this cast because they were so great together as a team. There were even moments that I needed to use the bathroom but couldn't allow myself to do so because I didn't want to miss a bit of info. Thomas McCarthy has been an impressive director in the past years (I have no comment on his last movie The Cobbler that was panned since I haven't seen it yet but The Visitor and Win Win are really strong movies) and this brings a lot of his talents together in a well oiled machine. It has the simplicity that Win Win and The Visitor have but blending it in with the amazing script and the great ensemble, the machine works excellently in unison. I think my minor quibbles with the movie is that it does take some time to really get captivated with stuff that really didn't need to be explained to me for 20 or so minutes with minor character developments between these character's work relationships and how the whole office works together, I think it could have benefited by jumping right into the action. I also had issues with some of the framing of scenes that ended up with Mark Ruffalo only being scene from his nose down it just looked really awkward but that isn't something too bothersome of an overall strong movie. The movie is quite devastating as it develops more and more into a powerful final sequence showing how many places all over the world have been found guilty of the same things unraveled here, some closer to you than you think. Like I said earlier, this is one of those rare films that you kind of want to do some homework afterwords to discover for yourself if something like this ever happened with your archdiocese, I was a bit reserved on the amount of praise this movie was getting from critics and being lauded as an awards frontrunner because the movie is about journalist and critics (for the most part) are journalist so it is a bit bias but I believe them though I don't know if it will go all the way. This is a must see movie that will make you shake your heads and interject throughout.
