Exceptional...attention getter from start to finish!!!
This is an incredibly complicated and important story to tell.  A monumental task, much like the work done by the reporters in a secretive department called Spotlight at the Boston Globe.   The writers and directors pull it off flawlessly.  Add some terrific performances by Mark Ruffalo and Michael Keaton and you now have a very Oscar worthy movie.  You will leave the theatre frustrated and angry at the systematic cover ups perpetrated by the Catholic Church. ..which is the point....and will also wonder how yourself and nobody new of the enormity of the abuse that was finally uncovered.  I was on the edge of my seat for the entire movie.  Incredibly acted and directed.
At its heart the quintessential ensemble film, McCarthy is very much focused on the investigative journalistic process circa Y2K, which shapes the very plot-driven film.  The screenplay thus leaves very little in the way of character development, keeping the action rather continuous and sweeping.   There is at times moments for actual contemplation about the whole weight of the issue at hand (Ruffalo, Keaton and Tucci), but these scenes are more "breathing spots" that segue-way to the next path of investigation. 

Watching the film, one can only wonder how a story (and subject matter) would have been handled just 10 years later in a more digital-based industry (more or less swiftly?).  Ultimately, McCarthy wants the viewer to understand that bricks-and-mortar journalism will always have a place in matter regardless of era or  issue at hand.
A stellar ensemble sells a strong script that doesn't bop the viewer on the nose with the enough-said obviousness of the injustices at work here.  It's a nice ode to the elbow grease and determination of journalism and the forces that beat on integrity along the way.  It also humanizes the focal journalists enough to see how a story that big - the now infamous child abuse scandals in the Catholic church - affects each one of them in different, jarring, personal ways.  With that grounded approach for our protagonists and the narrative momentum inherent with needing to pull the curtains back on this awful phenomena, the movie was engaging and mostly stirring throughout.  Strong film.
