This movie has a wholly unstylized approach to its subject, which in a way makes it journalistic and truer to its source material. Nothing is overly "cinematic" about Spotlight, which lets the vital details come through clearly. I'm glad this incredibly important story is reaching audiences in a new way.
"Spotlight" tells the horrific story of a sex scandal that manages to provide plenty of realistic and scary moments that will keep you intrigued, yet shocked.

"Spotlight" follows the story of a Boston Globe investigation into the case of a Catholic sex scandal involving a priest. As they look deeper into the case, they will have to fight through many overwhelming battles, as we get to watch how the story unfolds at the palm of our hands.

To start out, I want to give congrats to this movie for the realistic elements that it brought to the table. It managed to tell this story in an honorable way, and one that really justified what these people did for the United States. This movie feels very real in every way, and it feels like I'm there with these characters rather than watching them. Considering the nature of the story and its factual basis, the director and writers approached this story in a respectable manner, and I would be missing out if I hadn't seen this film.

The acting in this movie truly is a sight to see. Considering this movie feels very real and tamed, the acting that goes with it must match. There are a lot of big name actors in here, but they manage to make me forget about their names, and I see them as actual people. The amount of effort these actors/actresses put into it was great, and I felt like I was watching the actual people go through the actual situation. I felt like Mark Ruffalo's performance stood out the most, but all around, the cast was perfect. You have Mark Ruffalo, Michael Keaton, Rachel McAdams, Liev Schreiber,  Stanley Tucci, and more. What else could you ask for?

Let me get one thing straight, and it's that nothing really flashy happens in this movie. This is a film that is meant to depict a true story and it sticks to its facts. It doesn't over exaggerate anything and people who find dialogue and story telling dis-interesting will be bored out of their minds. I'll admit, this film had some boring moments where literally nothing was happening, so many people will be bothered by this.

The beginning felt kind of slow and flat to me, as nothing really had much purpose. As things started to unravel and they started getting deeper into the case, I was more interested, but until then, the movie wasn't mind blowing by any means.

You should probably watch this movie for the story alone, as there are many great aspects to it. There were multiple times where my jaw was on the ground and the revelations in this case were shocking. I never realized the severity of the situation, and this movie really does take its subject seriously.

There are even a few emotional and very deep moments that really make you think a lot. What these reporters did was huge, as they really helped point out a major corruption within the United States, and they truly deserve recognition. Knowing that these victims actually went through these situations and had to deal with this emotional agony affected me in many ways, and my heart goes out to those who had to live through this.

In the end, "Spotlight" is a quality production with many great aspects. I certainly had a great time with it, even if it was slightly underwhelming for my expectations. However, I feel as though this is the kind of film that will get better as time goes on, but for now, it will earn a solid 4 stars.
