This might be the smartest and most focused film of the year. Many people of my generation take this event for granted but Spotlight reminds us that this shook the Catholic Church and the Boston community to the core. Smartly acted by Keaton, McAdams, Ruffalo and Tucci, the film never glamorizes any aspect of the investigation. The reporters aren't super-spies risking their lives. The victims aren't exploited for audience-tears and their pain isn't put on display to shock you. But it's the handling of the Catholic church's role in the investigation/cover-up that Spotlight nails. Not at any time does the film damn the Vatican or Catholics for the actions of its clergy, but neither does it excuse the actions of the guilty parties.

Make no mistake: This is not a thriller, nor is it docu-drama. This is smart, focused, intelligent story-telling with a great ensemble cast that pulls you into it's story and never lets go.
