5 out of 5 stars.  An exceptional film, that will be viewed as this generation's "All the President's Men."  It may be the Best Picture Oscar winner for 2015, along with Best Director for Tom McCarthy and Supporting Actor for Michael Keaton.  Mark Ruffalo will also be recognized, although with top billing, he may be in the lead category, despite the ensemble nature of the cast work.

"Spotlight" is superbly written, acted and directed with dozens of actors making strong impressions, even in one-scene roles.  It's about a "big" issue - the Catholic Church cover up of priests molesting children in Boston.  Eventually the scandal rocked the Vatican's reputation worldwide.  However, the sordid nature of the topic is dealt with in a dignified & serious manner, so the film is never salacious or exploitative, where in lesser hands, it could have been.

The film is also an ode to investigative journalism, a rapidly vanishing profession of going for the deeper systemic story, not just the glossy superficial veneer of today's standard coverage.  The four-journalist Spotlight team begins casually on the story only to become obsessed with finding justice as the corruption widens into thousands of victims molested by dozens of priests.  Set in 2001-02, the period details are right, although this is not a film that will win Costume or Production Design awards, because it is more interested in the content than the look it's recreating.

Because of the subject matter and the serious depiction, this is not a blockbuster film as many Marvel or Disney films are this year.  It is a film that will be respected by all who see it, but not adored because this is a topic that makes everyone uncomfortable.  But if you like great writing, acting & directing, it is definitely an experience you will find rewarding.
The pedophile priest scandal was very bad. And sadly, so is this movie. Most critics love it. They're wrong. It was billed as a "thriller". It's not. No suspense at all.  It views more like a cartoon take-down of the evil Catholic Church (insert cheers here). And the acting is solid wood: The big shot at high emotion is the "It's Time!" (to destroy Cardinal Law) speech by Ruffalo's character, and, as Oscar Wilde might have put it, you'd have to have a heart of stone not to laugh at the overwrought dramatics. 

And some niggling questions remain: Has there ever been an infantile priest like the one in this movie who confesses his crime to Rachel McAdam - on the doorstep in mere seconds! Is Rachel's character guilty of elder abuse when she shows her dear old grannie, a three-times-a-week church-goer, the shocking news about the scandal in her church? That little silent scene must be the most ludicrous polemical overkill in the history of movies. And why is Michael Keaton's character surprised that so many people call in claiming clerical abuse after the big story breaks? Isn't he supposed to be a hard-nosed journo?

Oh, Oscar, Oscar! Sort it all out for us, please.
