This is the best kind of procedural drama, where the director and company tie all the strands of a complex story together without losing the audience for a moment.  With six strong supporting actors and not one of them playing lead, this is also the purest and most exciting performance ensemble that you'll find at the multiplex.  
Facts and clues and victims unfold at a growing pace as you listen in on interviews with corrupt lawyers, pedophiles, and long-suffering victims until It reaches all the way to the Vatican.  
Spotlight plays like a detective thriller but also succeeds at resonating on a deep emotional level.  It's exciting and exquisitely written and directed, but the heart and soul of the film lies in the real-life survivors and the reporters who all put their lives on hold in a desperate attempt to tell the whole truth.  
Spotlight ranks as one of the year's finest.  Highly recommended.
