A terrific film telling a devastating story. Everyone should see it.
So, I was a little on the younger side (10-12), and at a Catholic grade school when all of this blew up. Not only in Boston, but in my diocese of Cleveland. I remember it being a big deal, but also it not being really acknowledged. I can honestly say that this movie opened up my eyes to how truly terrible this epidemic was/still is. The depth of it is truly astounding. This also shed light on how the big systems (think government, big businesses, the church, etc.) control so many aspects of our lives. It took an outsider coming into this paper to really take stock of what was going on and push for the story. Basically, this movie made me do a lot of thinking. So, I guess its safe to say that this is a really well-made movie. The acting is great, the pacing is really tight, and the writing is awesome. Something I really respected was that the writing didn't fall into any movie traps. There was no character with a harrowing back story with a priest, and the facts weren't stretched to make it more "interesting". The story of these reporters was told truthfully, in the same way that they told their story, truthfully and to the point. Basically, I have a lot of respect for this movie and I believe that it deserves every nomination it received.
It never tries to assert itself as more important than the subject matter its tackling, and is all the more real and heartbreaking because of it.
Spotlight is a well written, well acted and a well directed drama of a real fact-based story that exposes one of biggest scandals of history of the catholic church. The Director Tom McCarthy builds a intriguing narrative that involves the audience with a shocking and horrifying revelations. Plus: The cast is marvelous. (4,5/5)
An often powerful, albeit conventional, ensemble drama, that should be a shoe-in for awards season front-runner. Dealing with some rather harrowing subject matter, Spotlight refrains from being off-putting by having the riveting nature of a good piece of journalism. Tom McCarthy directs the film with a 70s-esque sense (certain to give it even more comparisons to All the President's Men), and commands great performance from his troupe of thespians. It's too much of a stereotypical "awards picture" for me to call it masterful, but it is a fully necessary film that calls for action against the atrocities of the Church.
This movie follows the Boston Globe investigative reporters who broke the Catholic priest molestation scandal. A terrific cast of veteran actors play the reporters and the film does a good job of tracking the true developments in the case.  Since the blogosphere has essentially killed real investigative reporters, it is good to get a look at what is lost by this occupation disappearing. The contrast between how the story was investigated here and the more shoddy reporting showcased in the recent "Truth" is striking also.  This was a very good film.
