"Spotlight" is a "based on true events" film done right. McCarthy's slyly prosaic direction lets the factual events speak for themselves with little -if any- fluff injected. The cast is brilliant with particular nods to Keaton, Tucci, and Ruffalo; the latter of whom has had quite a year with this and "Infinitely Polar Bear". The brisk pacing combined with superbly executed disclosures made for a nail-biting rollercoaster. When the film ended I could hardly believe that 2 hours had just passed. "Spotlight" may have the flair of a made for TV movie, but it's ability to coerce emotional resonance out of it's viewers by simply telling the truth is highly commendable and can easily be regarded by this reviewer as one of the best films of the year. 4.5/5
Spotlight tells the story of an investigative reporting team named Spotlight, that is a branch of the Boston Globe. Under new direction from editor Marty Baron (Liev Schreiber), and superviser Ben Bradlee (John Slattery) the four members of Spotlight Walter Robinson (Michael Keaton), Mike Rezendes (Mark Ruffalo), Sasha Pfeiffer (Rachel McAdams) and Matt Caroll (Brian d'Arcy James) take off investigating reports of Catholic Priests molesting young boys.

Things I Liked:

The Cast. This movie has a stellar cast and they all give brilliant performances. In addition to the people who work at the Boston Globe, there are fantastic supporting performances from a number of other cast member including Stanley Tucci and Billy Crudup as lawyers Mitch Garabedian and Eric MacLeish. And a number of great performances from people who even I don't recognize. If there hard to be a standout it's Mark Ruffalo but the entire cast in this movie really works.

The Poignancy. The longer the movie goes on and the more you learn about the conspiracy the more startling it is when you realize that this is a true story. The other part of that is before the credits roll they show what other cities have been affected by the corruption in the church and it's startling to see the city you are currently living in on the list. The movie really hits home in those final moments and the entire thing speaks out about how even the most sacred of institutions can be corrupted.

The Story. The investigation is impressive as the whole thing moves along. The movie has a tension and an excitement and you really find the entire thing interesting which is impressive for a movie that does nothing but show conversations between people. The movie is not one for people who need explosions, or stunts, but the movie has a phenomenal use of story to keep readers interested. It's a great thing to watch.

Things I Didn't Like:

No Comment. The movie is solid. I personally didn't have anything about it that really dragged it down. They say this is one of the heaviest hitters in the Oscar race and I can see why. It's a solid movie.

Overall:

Overall the movie is really well done. It tells an interesting story. The cast all deliver great performance. The movie really tells an important story that hits home even if you don't have any true personal connection to what has happened. It's a great movie that really works on every level and I am predicting this one is gonna be heavy contender come awards season. A fantastic piece of cinematic storytelling.
While the first act may stutter a few times and some aspects of the story involving witnesses and the psychological side never fully develop, Spotlight is an impeccable feat as both an intelligent reporter story and an incredible film.
One of the few movies I will watch again.  It was so well done.
