Amazing. Hopefully an Oscar winner for 4 leads and best picture. Must see for Catholics still naive to this awful truth, including myself.
I had the opportunity to catch a sneak screening of this film a week prior to its release and want to draw some attention to it and its undeniable quality as it will likely, ironically enough, fail to ever find the spotlight butting head-to-head with Spectre being released the same weekend.  There will always (arguably) be another James Bond movie or over-the-top action film similar to it, but Spotlight is a rare film this year that would be a shame to miss and deserves every bit of attention it will likely receive come award season.

Spotlight is a film imbued with an intrinsic sense of subtlety and deference.  It doesn't dwell on Hollywood-isms or trick the audience with convenient plot twists and escapist subplots and drama.  Spotlight is, at its core, bare-knuckled, by-the-books, calculated, and precisely executed.  It only reaches as far as the scope of the story that inspired the film demands.  As a minor consequence, it can come off as dry and somber at times, but this film has so many other things going for it that it never really seems to drag.

If Spotlight had been told in any other way with any other cast, it likely would have either parted from a truthful, realistic depiction of the actual events or came across as the largest bore of 2015.  To be fair, however, the story itself is compelling in its own right and is likely to relate to any audience member bold enough to sit through a film of this type.  It was actually a very dense film with little intrigue beyond the cast and premise, but it was told in such a convincing way that to give it anything other than my full attention would have felt disrespectful.  It really felt like it was just a few great acting performances away from actually turning into a documentary, and likely would have been just as effective as such.

So let's get into what really matters in a film of this style and caliber:  the performances.  As one would expect given the rave reviews of the film already and the names attached to this title, the performances are spectacular all around.  Michael Keaton has toned down from his over-dramatic, schizophrenic Birdman role to a far more calm, self-serious, motivated character in Spotlight.  Keaton's character, however, is never really given a chance to shine and pales in comparison to the character played by Mark Ruffalo who, in my opinion, stole the show.  He plays his typical investigation-related role that he's played at least ten times now, although his performance reminded me most clearly of not his, but Jake Gyllenhaal's character in Zodiac.  Instead of calm and suave as per usual, he now plays the overly passionate, sociopathic type that doesn't seem to get a wink of rest from the start to the end of the film in so desperately trying to uncover the mystery beneath it all.  Rachel McAdams is great, too.  And it only feels right for her to be in this, immediately following her role in the second season of True Detective which was likewise plagued by the complication of dealing with too many indistinguishable names and characters.

I should sidetrack briefly and admit to one flaw I felt fell upon the movie a bit for me and that was the complication of dealing with so many different leads, victims, alleged criminals and so on and so forth.  It would be criminal not to include all of these names as they all served as individual cogs used to propel the narrative along.  I just almost wish they weren't introduced at such a rapid pace, or at least that each name was given equal weight.  I nodded my head at the times where characters would recall details of the person being described to help me remember him or her, but other times so many names of people never physically shown on camera would be thrown in the mix simply for the purpose of reference that I began to find myself a little lost.  Perhaps that's just me.  I just felt at times characters didn't elaborate upon perceptibly crucial details as well as some procedural films similar to it.

Nevertheless, each character portrayed felt human, emotionally charged and vibrant, relatable, and important.  Spotlight did such a good job portraying each character and just enough detail of their back stories evenly that it's almost hard to say who the main character of the film really even was.  An argument could be made somewhere between Ruffalo, Keaton, and McAdams, but even between the three of them each character is covered to a pretty even degree.  I loved that about this movie because it helped everything seem level.  No one character was heralded or glamorized above another and each member of the Boston Globe editorial team portrayed contributed to the development of the narrative in their own unique ways, as it would have been in reality.

This film is tonally consistent, fair and respectful of its subject matter, emotionally driven, well-acted, thought-provoking, deftly-paced, and even appears to have an exceptional sense of direction both in terms of narrative and style.  Director Tom McCarthy handled the true story perfectly in a way that never came off as expository or shameful, but rather enlightening and powerful.  All around Spotlight is a well-made, tightly-crafted, and tense drama revolving around a topic that threatens to shake society's faith of the religious institution, as it did for me.  They don't make many movies quite like this anymore.  With the attention span of much of the modern audience there isn't much room for attention to be drawn to this type of film anymore outside of Oscar buzz, and the box office numbers prove it time and again.  So do Hollywood some justice and see BOTH Spectre AND Spotlight on November 6th when they're released in the US.
Really Powerful and Compelling. A cast at the top of their game and a director/screenwriter making sure you are evoked and as the cast is uncovering truths and lies, your just as perplexed as to what they should do as reporters. One of the years best.
Intelligent suspenseful drama covers the incredibly complex project taken on by the Boston Globes Spotlight investigative reporters, to uncover a child sexual abuse scandal by the Catholic Church so enormous in scope, there is a continuous string of pauses throughout just to allow us to grasp the idea, along with the characters.  It is fast paced, brilliantly cast, sharply written, nail bitingly suspenseful, gripping, and smart.  Best movie so far this year.
I'd be quite happy for this to win the Oscar. Excellent.
SPOTLIGHT is that rare film that takes a true event and delves into it with razor-sharp focus while employing a straightforward no-nonsense approach; it refuses to resort to ubiquitous movie-like scenarios - there is no fluff, no dazzle, no unnecessary drama, no corny subplots, and none of those moments we have come to associate with "cheesy" and "Hollywood." Instead, what Tom McCarthy has brought to the table is a tightly written script about work and process - the ensemble is excellent as they merge into their real-life counterparts and bring to life the strategies and dedication and sacrifice their characters must go through in order to reach their desired outcome (while fighting against the Catholic Church, no less). This is easily one of the least flashy but most thrilling and rejuvenating films of the year.
Well done, good performances and an original approach at the beginning of 2000. Spotlight proves to be a well-made film with a complex argument about pederasty and a controversial message for the Catholic society, the truth will not hide for long.
Exemplifying the pillars of journalistic integrity, Spotlight provides one of the most intense situations in recent domestic American history, the Catholic church, and multiple lawyers, being questioned in their defense of sanctioned pedophilia and its victims. From the opening shot, the fluidity between actors is well displayed, the spotlight team (comprised of Keaton, Ruffalo, McAdams, and James), working in tandem with one another, the script and performance of each actor giving an eerily natural flow from one scene to the next. Schreiber and Slattery don't have as much screen time as the aforementioned, but their unique characters give enough oomph to the plot line. With a muted piano & bass-heavy score, only the sounds of the streets of Boston as well as the office of The Boston Globe to accompany the sound profile, the film in itself is an edge-of-the-seat dramatic piece. The reason I believe it's one of the best films I've seen in a very long time is resonant in the fact that it characterizes the sheer tenacity of integrous/virtuous journalists, rooting through the murky legislation and human will that surrounds this scandal. A must watch.
Very good movie a little slow in beginning but hit it's stride and kept interest rest of way out.   Excellent acting.
A profound film both in vision and storytelling that includes one of the best ensembles of the year, Spotlight avoids the cliches and over-the-top antics to provide true and informative journalism. The end result is both real and gripping, making Spotlight one of the best films of the year. 9.5/10
