I'm sure there are people  who will resist Knowing what this movie discloses. Unfortunately, unless these people who want to stick their head in the sand see this by accident, it's preaching mostly to the choir. But everyone should see this. Back in 2002, when this story broke, it led to a flood of thousands of people all over the world coming forward with their stories. SEVEN sons in just ONE family were affected, and still the family kept the secret. This is not just a story of exposing corruption, it is about exposing the most heinous of Crimes, with an entire Institution, everyday families, politicians, police, lawyers, etc. involved in the cover up.
Easily the best film I've watched this year. in an age where true journalism is too often crowded out by attention grabbing headline soundbites, this movie reminds readers of the purpose of journalism: to seek, understand, and declare the Truth by breaking down the institutions that profit by hiding it.
Being Michael Keaton's first film since the Best Picture winning Birdman or (The Unexpected Virtue of Ignorance), Spotlight had promises of strong acting.

Though my original intentions for watching Spotlight came from the presence of Michael Keaton, I discovered something far more impressive lying in the roots of the film. Directed and written by Thomas McCarthy, Spotlight is a promising return to form after his abysmal effort on the Golden Raspberry Award nominated The Cobbler (2014). In one of, if not his greatest film to date, Spotlight presents the man an opportunity to transcend a new level of brilliance without betraying his true nature as an independent filmmaker. He exceeds these standards with a tenacious grip over truthful storytelling and genuine entertainment.
Though The Cobbler had a low budget, it still presents a time when Tom McCarthy sold out. In Spotlight, the man returns to what he is good at and manages to divert a collection of accomplished Hollywood actors in a film far from the narrative dramatization and studio interference of the Hollywood system. He makes a film which is very clear in its goal and simple in its path. Spotlight is a feature so focused on narrative that it neglects the need to highlight the appearances of its stars or even create much imagery. The actors are predominantly toned down to maintain a more everyman appearance, which can vary from the natural appearances of Michael Keaton and Mark Ruffalo to the less glamourized appearance of natural beauty Rachel McAdams and beyond to a nearly unrecognizable Liev Schreiber. The only real moments of imagery come from the few shots which capture the images of churches in a fashion which subtly depicts the size of them and symbolizes the scope of their strength in the process. The visual style of the film is simple, giving a more realistic edge to it and challenging the actors to perform with minimal editing and more prolonged shots. The technical aspects of Spotlight do not dominate but are fairly solid with the use of a subtle musical score being gently atmospheric, and though the audio feed has some occasional moments of being a little rough, it is hardly enough to damage the experience.
Spotlight is a film which is so rich in narrative that it relies solely on actual storytelling to keep the viewer engaged.  To support this, the screenplay is full of tenacious dialogue and many themes to cover. There is a lot to keep up with which can overload viewers while the slow pace put in to give them time to comprehend everything can also make it drag on a bit, but ultimately it is difficult not to get caught up in the narrative because the dialogue is so rich that it gives the film characters, concepts and themes which just keep coming. There is rarely a dull moment in the film, and though it is very talkative there are always interesting topics of discussion. Spotlight chronicles serious subject matter: the story of The Boston Globe's investigation into systemic child sex abuse in the Boston area at the hands of the Catholic Church. Though it does not get too deeply into the material to rely on psychological melodrama to drive its narrative, it doesn't play it safe either. The film finds an effective balance in the multiple perspectives taken on the events. Audiences are given a chance to hear the experiences of victims discussing what they experienced, how it affected them or why it allowed them to happen as well as the investigators searching them for answers. There is also the perspective of members of the church and those within the legal system who contributed to hiding things or attempted to take a stand. There is a broad scope of material in Spotlight and strong characters to sustain it rather than a reliance on style. The slow pace of the story is not a major problem because things keep moving along between the main story and the multiple characters, with the main figures being essentially equal in relevance at all times. As a result, the actors are given plenty of room to breathe and flex their dramatic muscles which leaves the determination of the best characters to rely almost solely on the performances of the actors.
Mark Ruffalo is surely the screen stealer. In an Academy Award nominated performance, Mark Ruffalo consistently conveys a level of sophisticated intelligent and professionalism in his part where he engages with the fellow characters as both associates and friends. He therefore captures a realistic sense of humanity and friendliness in the part, but that is only a subcategory of his extensive talent. Mark Ruffalo is constantly on an ambitious quest for truth in Spotlight with more intense determination than any of the actors around him. He highlights the tense nature of the atmosphere through the ability to speak very fast but also clearly. He manages to put many extents of emotion into all this, ranging from internal to physical. His engagement in the role is very rich, and it hits its endeavour at the most dramatic moment in the film. The deeper his character Michael Rezendes gets into the investigation, the more it becomes personal and Mark Ruffalo capitalizes on that in one scene where he confronts Walter "Robby" Robinson with a desire to pursue an immediate story and becomes aggressive by the lack of support. He shouts his way into immediately capturing the full attention of audiences and catapults himself into being the most interesting character of the story for the remainder of the film if he had not already established that for viewers, and it is another boost to the credibility of the actors' already many achievements. Mark Ruffalo delivers one of his career's finest performances in Spotlight, and his Academy Award nomination is well-deserved.
Michael Keaton is also brilliant. Though he is not given nearly as much personal insight, Michael Keaton commands the Spotlight team with a natural sense of leadership about him. He maintains a great understanding of all the legal concepts and ethical dilemmas of his situation and conveys it with sophistication and charm, confidently speaking every word without a second thought. He stands strong in the role and creates strong interactions with the surrounding cast, particularly the aforementioned climax with Mark Ruffalo. Michael Keaton's performance in Spotlight is yet another reminder of just what great talent has resurged with his career comeback.
Rachel McAdams is also brilliant. Capturing the same rich sense of determination maintained by her fellow Spotlight team members, Rachel McAdams' speciality lies in the ability to convey that strength while also having a gentle side. Her interactions with certain characters prove to be very subtle in drama, yet she highlights a rich emotional state for the duration of them without pushing into melodrama or tedious sentimentality. In one of her greatest performances to date, Rachel McAdams is powerfully intelligent and ambitious yet one of the most human characters of the story and distinctive as a result. She adds her own style of drama to the film which is an essential element of the entertainment and humanity of the story, resulting in one of the finest performances of her career.
John Slattery is also a dedicated member of the cast, and Liev Schreiber's restraint and sophistication in an almost-unrecognizable getup is most admirable. 

So Spotlight is a talkative and gently paced film, rich with Tom McCarthy's tenacious direction over an intelligent screenplay that covers essential subject matter, all while remaining bolstered by a brilliant cast led by Mark Ruffalo's incredible talents.
