Intriguing, beautifully scripted and gripping newspaper investigation. Spotlight takes audiences into a moment that everyone can relate to: a time in which telling the truth about a matter is both necessary and perilous.
This movie/story is one that definitely needs to be told, and the acting is great, particularly by Ruffalo, but I would be lying if I said I didn't get really bored at times during this film. It just comes off as a bone dry film for the critics to drool over. The film develops well and is interesting in spurts, but I wouldn't recommend this one for entertainment. Perhaps if you have a particular interest in the subject matter you will enjoy it more than I did.
Hands-down, the best film I saw this past year... by far. If you're looking for a film the leaves you with a hopeful feeling by the closing credits, this definitely is not it. But for what it lacks in "happy feelies" it makes up for in the cold-hard truth of the hardships endured by victims of sexual abuse, as well as the incredulity of how long such incidents were swept under the rug for decades. The cast portraying the dedicated "Spotlight" team is the best I've seen since films like "Argo," "The King's Speech," and "The Social Network." Each person feeds off of the next with seamless fluidity. It's surprising that the cast standout, Michael Keaton, hasn't gotten more recognition compared to his puzzling role in "Birdman" - though Mark Ruffalo and Rachel McAdams did a very commendable job to earn supporting nominations. As a Christian, seeing stories of widespread exploitation condoned by a church institution leaves me nothing short of frustrated, disgusted, and disappointed. Nonetheless, I highly recommend more people of faith to see this film... for the sole reason that we need to understand and take ownership of such injustices if we're ever to be effective witnesses for His Kingdom.
It occasionally has the feel of a TV movie that was released in theaters, but I get that the straightforward direction is really about trying to avoid sensationalizing the story than any laziness on the part of the filmmakers. As a testament to the laborious and important process of serious investigative journalism, the movie works quite well.
