Forensic, dialogue-heavy and well-acted newspaper drama about the Catholic Church's ruthless cover-up of child abuse and paedophilia. What stops it being great is a certain airlessness and self-satisfaction: think what it might have been if the Church had been allowed more screen time. You'll need to engage your brain too, because the mumbled dialogue is often delivered at Howard Hawks speed.
Outstanding. I was not looking forward to this viewing but was taken back by the conviction and diligence of this true recounting of the Boston's Globe coverage of one of the biggest scandals of all time: Michael Keaton was riveting. Mark Ruffalo  brought what may be the best performance of his already stunning career. The rest of the cast also brought memorable performances: Rachel McAdams, Liev Schreiber, Jaime Sheridan and Stanley Tucci. Tucci's every twitch, ascant gaze and nod of his head felt genuine. I believed his character and this movie had the same genuineness. Spotlight is what journalism should strive to be and what many hope it will return to.
Refreshing to watch actors play intelligent people. It's smart, taut, slow-burning goodness. One of the year's best and a surefire Oscar contender. The whole ensemble is terrific, but I'm putting a little star next to Liev Schreiber's name. His understated performance as the new Boston Globe editor commanded the screen and anchors the film.
Spotlight is the greatest movie about investigative journalism since All The Presidents Men. It tells its story without any typical Hollywood cues or annoying subplots. It's the kind of film that will be shown in journalism classes as the perfect example of how to find and evaluate information to build a story. It's subject matter can get touchy for some, but it's hard to argue with hard facts. I didn't expect to see a film reach this level of excellence this year but Spotlight has managed to surpass it. It's already my pick for best picture and there are still many movies to watch this Oscar bait season.
