Spotlight flows a team of journalists at The Boston Globe who uncover the Catholic Church molestation scandal in 2001. Spotlight is a masterpiece of film making. It has a fantastic cast of Michael Keaton, Mark  Ruffalo, Rachael Mckadams, and Leiv Schreiber. Spotlight is a movie that everyone should see, and is one of the best films of 2015.
A film of this style is easily classified as generic, many films intend to be a denounce and finally say nothing. Spotlight goes further, providing a clever script that knows exactly the keys to understand the problem, with conviction and delicacy.
Fantastic docu-film centered around the massive news expose (and some 600 stories posted thereafter) published by the Boston Globe in the early 2000s surrounding the Catholic Church child molestation cases and subsequent cover-up dating back nearly 30 years... Being a part of the news industry I remember this story all too well and Spotlight did a fantastic job of bringing something new to the table as well as providing a 2+ hour entertaining movie along the way. Acting, writing, directing, and even the editing were all well done; if you care about journalism even just a little bit, or are intrigued by these types of slow-burn thriller films, you owe it to yourself to see Spotlight (in limited theater release now) as its up there in my favorites of 2016 and I see a bright future for this film come award season...
A superb film with a fantastic ensemble cast!
