Like a modern day All the President's Men, Spotlight is a superb look into the importance of investigative journalism, told gracefully by wonderful performances, sharp editing, and an incredible script. This true story about one investigative team at The Boston Globe and how they uncovered a decades long cover up of sexual assault in the Catholic Church is one of the best films of the year. It showcases how great journalism is important, hard work, and above all: necessary.
Right away, Spotlight is poised to be totally attracting to the Oscars. Its ripped-from-the-headlines story, its impressive cast, and serious subject matter make it a prime contender for several Academy Award categories. Making a movie about the journalistic investigation of the Catholic Church's sex scandals needs to result in a strong movie to avoid being annoying or exploitative. Although not as impressive as one would be led to believe, Spotlight is a strongly acted and well written movie, its subtlety building to a climax just like its real-life subject matter. Being a movie that's mostly based in stagnate locations--offices, apartments, etc.--Spotlight greatly benefits from its core talent. Its cast does a very good job as a whole, and although I wasn't blown away by anyone in particular, each person in front of the camera avoids overacting, save for one scene involving Mark Ruffalo (and his fake accent with a lisp). Rachel McAdams might be the most enjoyable to watch. She always has a great presence, but she's both strong and sympathetic. She kind of has a Dana Scully thing going on. The screenplay is interesting constructed in how it allows each sex abuse survivor to recount their stories, as well as how the movie's understated approach to the material mirrors how it was deflected by officials and publications in real life until it couldn't be ignored anymore. Thomas McCarthy's direction compliments the script well, but it isn't really anything to write home about. Despite its positives, Spotlight isn't a movie that works wonders, but simply because it doesn't noticeable surpass other movies as of late. There's nothing in particular that fails, but I won't probably won't find myself looking back at 2015 come last week of December saying, "Yeah, Spotlight was amazing. Top ten material there," or anything. It's not amazing, but it's still strong thanks to its performances and screenplay. I don't think that Spotlight will stick with me for a while, but it's still nothing short of solid. It's engaging and interesting, but not a ton past that. 7.9/10, solid, one thumb up, above average, etc.
