From one of my favorite production companies Participant Media. Boston in recent years seems to be taking New York's spot as THE cinematic city in which to uncover humanity's underbelly. Spotlight may not lionize the reporters, but they are admirable people doing honorable work, polar opposites of the reporters in the old play and movies The Front Page playing fast and loose with the facts of a case. Billed as an ensemble piece, there are uniformly solid performances from each member of the cast, however Mark Ruffalo, as Mike Rezendes, delves a bit deeper into his character, perhaps has the greatest share of screen time, and delivers the biggest emotional punch. A true story powerfully told!
Spotlight is a news drama film directed and co-written by Tom McCarthy and it stars Mark Ruffalo, Michael Keaton, Rachel McAdams, and Liev Schreiber in a true story about a team that works for The Boston Globe called Spotlight, and they were investigating about child sex abuse from multiple Catholic Priests and make a story out of what's going on. I've heard tons and tons of good things about this, even calling it one of the best films of 2015. I still kept it on an open mind though, but was still excited to see it no matter what. I've also never heard of this story before, so I also want to keep that open for it too, and after watching it, people were right as Spotlight is one of the best films that I've seen in 2015. The cast are excellent in it and definitely act like news investigators by keeping their cool and patient while still caring about the story that they want to dig deep on, even if it's their job to do. It has a great story, and it takes advantage on the details of it that really doesn't feel like it's Hollywoodized. Even if there were some details that were in the story but not in the movie, I'm still impressed about how it still looks and feels like I'm watching an original film. The writing by Tom McCarthy and Josh Singer is so well-written and felt like real dialogue to me, and the characters are very three-dimensional. I did like how it was addressed that doing a news on the Catholic Church is very difficult as they would probably find out about it and they are pretty much everywhere. I wasn't as mad as I thought was going to be with the twists as it was because I watched a documentary about a child molester priest, but I was still as surprised at it as the characters in the movie were also when they found out about it. What they did at the ending is very respectful and does need to be more well known. Spotlight is a fantastic film that is probably the biggest step up that I've seen from critics dreading his previously film The Cobbler, to loving Spotlight.
