It feels like it's been a while since I've seen an intelligent movie. One that made me want to do something. One of the best lines was from the special features, talking about how news has become more entertainment based and good journalism and journalists are becoming less and less. This movie is certainly a motivation to get off you YouTube top ten lists and figure out what's really going on around us.
One of the films about journalism sense all the president's men.
Spotlight is the most consistently solid film I've seen in a long, long time. Every other film I've seen this year has had at least one part that I didn't like, one scene where I wasn't convinced, one performance that bothered me. But Spotlight has none of these things. It is constantly engaging, smart but not so much that it makes the audience feel dumb. It has a perfect balance of emotion and procedure, shining a light on the Spotlight team itself as well as letting the audience feel for those affected by the molestation they are investigating. It is an ensemble piece, and boy does everyone shine - Michael Keaton and Mark Ruffalo both give Oscar-worthy performances, but every single person on screen rises to the occasion and gives noteworthy and admirable performances. Thomas McCarthy directs the hell out of the film, too. Every stylistic choice resonates, and he is amazing at finding the human in every character, from giving them personal ticks to representing their motives without directly stating them to a potentially overwhelmed audience. The editing is fantastic, the score understated but perfect in tone, the cinematography non intrusive but effective. Spotlight may not be the most emotionally resonating film of the year (though it does invoke a lot of great emotional response), but it is the most expertly made, directed, and presented film in years.
Phenomenal. A must-see look into one of the most confrontational stories of the century.
Excellent movie,  incredible cast. Definitely worth it!
A film that demands to be seen

Spotlight is the staggering and insightful story about the investigation behind Catholic priest child abuse. It is an absolutely horrifying look into the darkest secrets of the Catholic Church that will make parishioners rethink their position on whether they could trust in what they're doing. The fact that they may have known or been to places where these people have took charge is unsettling. 

This film is absolutely fantastic. It hits all the right notes and is clearly going to be a frontrunner in the Oscar race this season. Everyone in the cast is on their A-game, and the script and direction makes up a powerful and fascinating story. There is so much this film had to address and it does it so in a very compelling fashion.

On the other hand this film does not deal with the aftermath of the situation. It may have been nice to learn how the Church dealt with this after the word went out to the world. Some supporting characters may have been clarified also, with more screen time they may have been more than plot devices.

Overall this is one of the best films of the year. Keaton, Ruffalo, McAdams, and the rest of the cast make up one of the best ensembles to be onscreen for the year as well. McCarthy does a great job telling the story and does his best to not make it feel overly dramatized, which films with sensitive subjects do sometimes. Spotlight is a film that needs to be seen.

Rating: 8.5 (A)
Spotlight may be a bit to restrained to really deliver the full effect its going for it remains a very timely and scary piece of cinema. 
