Paced well and truly invigorating. Spotlight's cast does wonders in this mystery-drama and proves why this won best picture. The pacing of the film was flawless and the dialogue was top notch. Really gives you a lot to think about when the credits start rolling. Outstanding film!
'Spotlight' is harrowing, tightly directed, and sharply written, but what makes it truly exceptional is the cast. This is a collection of powerhouse performances in which every actor brings their best to the table. Mark Ruffalo and Stanley Tucci are spellbinding.
Spotlight is a movie for people who love dialogue driven scripts and phenomenal acting. I went into Spotlight having no previous knowledge of the source material or its background, so I was excited to learn more of the story and get angry at myself for not knowing about the story earlier. If I could describe Spotlight in one word, it'd definitely be enthralling. I was completely engaged in the story and all the research that was being done throughout the film. It's hard to make a movie like this not boring because you have to cast the right people, write an interesting enough script while staying faithful to source material, and keep an even pace. Spotlight did all of those things and made it exciting. There was never a dull moment throughout the runtime and that's mainly due to the exceptionally strong ensemble of actors. Michael Keaton, Rachel McAdams, Mark Ruffalo, Liev Schreiber, John Slattery, Stanley Tucci, as well as the remaining cast were all fantastic and Oscar worthy as well! They delivered their smart, sometimes witty dialogue in such a demanding and sleek manner that it was impossible to not be interested in what they were addressing. The dialogue as a whole was really well written, like I said it's hard to make a movie like this as interesting as it was. The story is also really well crafted with its writing too. The Boston Globe finding unveiled information about multiple child molestation cases by catholic priests sounds interesting enough, but when you watch the cast uncover the new, shocking information it's just so fun to watch. My one small issue I have with this film is that it was hard to keep up with all the names that are stated. I remember all the main peoples' names but there were a few characters that popped up for a scene or two, but their names are still being used. It jittered me up for a few minutes but that's really my only complaint. The story never managed to get dull, in fact, it gets really intense as it progresses. There's a scene with Mark Ruffalo where he's trying to get these documents for their news article that's extremely intense and even stressful to watch. The timeline of this movie is really spot on too, there's scenes of winter time, spring, and even 9/11 to remind you what year this went down. That was a real clever touch. In the very end, I couldn't tell if I should be angry or happy. The way the film wrapped up was well done, but something happens during the credits that was jaw dropping. Spotlight is an experience to BE experienced. It has one of the best casting ensembles I've ever seen, fantastic story telling, a really interesting story TO tell, and it actually made me feel smarter after watching. A-
Strong performances drive a strong story in a film that reminds me, in tone, of All The President's Men. This also reminds me of why the world needs newspapers. There is no other media outlet that has ever committed the time, money or manpower that print does to serving the community.
A story that needed to be told. A must watch. Hats off to the Spotlight team that uncovered the travesty, but nothing Oscar worthy from the cast.